'''Matteo I Visconti''' (1250 – 24 June 1322) was the second of the Milanese [[Visconti of Milan|Visconti]] family to govern [[Milan]].{{sfn|Campbell|2003}} Matteo was born to [[Teobaldo (o Tibaldo) Visconti|Teobaldo Visconti]] and Anastasia Pirovano.

In 1287, Matteo's uncle [[Ottone Visconti]], [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Milan|archbishop]] and first lord of Milan, nominated him as ''[[capitano del popolo]]'' of Milan. Following his uncle's death in 1295, he succeeded him as lord of Milan. Matteo was appointed numerous times as [[Imperial Vicar]] over the whole of [[Lombardy]], while expanding, with the assistance of his sons, his [[sphere of influence]] to [[Piedmont]], [[Emilia (region of Italy)|Emilia]], [[Bologna]], and [[Genoa]]. Caught between the Papal and Imperial power struggle over northern Italy, Matteo would renounce his imperial title as "General Lord of the Milanese People". Found guilty on the charge of [[necromancy]], [[excommunication|excommunicated]], and facing a crusade, Matteo resigned his position and died months later. He was succeeded by his son [[Galeazzo I Visconti|Galeazzo I]].

==Life==

===The early years===
Matteo was the son of [[Teobaldo Visconti (1230-1276)|Teobaldo Visconti]], and the great-nephew of the first lord (that is, governor) of Milan, [[Ottone Visconti]].{{sfn|Campbell|2003}} His mother was Anastasia Pirovano.{{sfn|Benedetti|2009|p=26}} In August, 1269, Matteo married [[Bonacossa Borri]].{{sfn |Paoletti |Radke |1997 |p=452}} His great-uncle Ottone appointed him ''[[Capitano del Popolo]] [Captain of the People]'' of Milan, after winning the battle of Desio in 1277.{{sfn|Gamberini|2014|p=22}}{{sfn|Williman|2010}} In 1289 and 1294, the citizens of Milan re-elected him Captain of the people.{{sfn|Clarke|2016|p=122}}

===Imperial influence===
Following the death of [[William VII, Marquess of Montferrat]] in 1292, Matteo expanded his influence westward, taking Casale, gaining the lordships of [[Novara]] and [[Vercelli]], and the captaincy of [[Alessandria]].{{sfn|Armstrong|1932|p=[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.282060/page/n61 24]}} His expansion was temporary as William's son, [[John I, Marquess of Montferrat|John of Monferrat]], re-took Alessandria and forced the [[Ghibellines]] out of Novara and Vercelli.{{sfn|Armstrong|1932|p=[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.282060/page/n61 24]}}

Despite this setback, Matteo was appointed Imperial Vicar of Lombardy in 1294 by [[Adolf, King of Germany|Adolf of Nassau]].{{sfn|Lee|2018|p=52}} The next year, after the death of Ottone, a period of struggle for domination of Milan began anew between the Ghibellines (the supporters of the Kings of the Romans and [[Holy Roman Emperor]]s and thus also of Matteo as Imperial Vicar) and the [[Guelphs and Ghibellines|Guelphs]], the partisans of the [[Pope]] led by the traditional enemies of the Visconti, the [[Della Torre]] family. In 1299, [[Albert I of Germany]] reappointed him as Imperial Vicar.{{sfn|Armstrong|1932|p=[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.282060/page/n61 24]}}
[[File:Visconti, Matteo Magno.jpg|thumb|left|Visconti, Matteo Magno]]
Matteo managed to remain at the helm of the city until June 1302, when [[Guido della Torre]] again took the lordship of Milan, through a league formed by the Torriani and the anti-Visconti families of the cities of [[Cremona]], [[Pavia]], [[Piacenza]], Novara, Vercelli, Lodi, Crema, and [[Monferrato]] led by Alberto Scotti and Ghiberto da Correggio.{{sfn|Armstrong|1932|p=[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.282060/page/n61 25]}} Matteo's home in Milan was attacked and looted. Forced into exile, Matteo remained for several years a guest of the [[Scaliger]] family at Nogarola ([[Motteggiana]]).{{sfn|Armstrong|1932|p=[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.282060/page/n61 25]}}

In 1311, Matteo met the [[German King]] [[Henry VII, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry VII]] at [[Asti]] and from this, received a mandate to reach a peace agreement in Lombardy.{{sfn|Starn|1982|p=56}} On 4{{nbsp}}December that year, Matteo and the archbishop [[Cassone della Torre]] signed an agreement.{{sfn|Starn|1982|p=56}} Between December 1310 and February 1311, the German King, who was crowned [[King of Italy]] on 6{{nbsp}}January by Cassone della Torre, tried to find common ground between the Torriani and Visconti.{{sfn|Armstrong|1932|p=[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.282060/page/n69 32]}} However, on 12{{nbsp}}February, German soldiers of Henry VII faced an armed Torriani force, led by Guido della Torre, who did not accept the treaty between their cousin Cassone and Matteo.{{sfn|Law|1995|p=443}} The King's forces prevailed and Guido della Torre fled Milan. Due to his suspected involvement in della Torre's downfall, Matteo was exiled for a time, but on 13{{nbsp}}July 1311 King Henry sold the title of imperial vicar for Milan to Matteo.{{sfn|Armstrong|1932|p=[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.282060/page/n69 33]}} They then organized a league that included Milan, Como, Novara, Vercelli, Bergamo, Brescia, Lodi, Cremona, and Piacenza, which had all become Ghibelline cities loyal to the Emperor. Just over a year later, the Emperor died on 24{{nbsp}}August 1313 at [[Buonconvento]] in [[Tuscany]].{{sfn|Herde|1995|p=536}} In 1314, claiming descent from the fictitious counts of Angera, Matteo occupied Angera castle, property of the archbishop of Milan.{{sfn|Dunlop|2009|p=177}}{{sfn|Marina|2013|p=379}} He commissioned a [[fresco]] in the main hall of the castle which illustrated the victory of the Visconti family over Napoleone della Torre at the [[battle of Desio]].{{sfn|Marina|2013|p=396}}

===Suppression of the Guelphs===
[[File:DSC02617 - Milano - Sant'Eustorgio - Dettaglio del fianco - Scultura e stemma - Foto di Giovanni Dall'Orto - 15-jan-2007.jpg|thumb|right|The bust and coat-of-arms of Matteo Visconti at the [[Basilica of Sant'Eustorgio]], in Milan. It is located on the outer wall of the chapel of St. Thomas, also known as Visconti Chapel. Visconti had it constructed in 1297 when he was 47 years old, and at this time his portrait was carved.]]Matteo, despite his lack of military talent, had warlike sons who were directly involved in the war against the Guelphs.{{sfn|Armstrong|1932|p=[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.282060/page/n81 44]}} In October 1315 Matteo's sons, Marco Visconti and [[Luchino Visconti (died 1349)|Luchino Visconti]] defeated the Tuscan Guelphs on the [[Scrivia|Scrivia River]] near [[Voghera]], which was followed by the capture of Pavia.{{sfn|Armstrong|1932|p=[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.282060/page/n81 45]}} This re-established Ghibelline control. For security, Matteo built a castle with a Milanese garrison in the city, captained by his son Luchino.{{sfn|Armstrong|1932|p=[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.282060/page/n81 45]}}

==Conflict with the Church==
In an attempt to halt imperial influence over northern Italy,{{sfn|Godthardt|2012|p=17}} Pope John XXII declared in his [[Papal bull|bull]] of 1317, ''Si fratrum'',{{sfn|Applauso|2018|p=134}} that anyone claiming the title "Imperial Vicar" without papal consent would be excommunicated.{{sfn|Armstrong|1932|p=45}} This bull was specifically directed at Matteo of Milan, Cangranda della Scala in Verona and Este in Ferrara.{{sfn|Herde|1995|pp=538–39}} In response, Matteo took the title "General Lord of the Milanese People".{{sfn|Armstrong|1932|p=[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.282060/page/n81 45]}} The pope appointed two emissaries, Bernard Gui and Bertrand de la Tour, to investigate the Ghibelline areas of Milan, [[Lombardy]], and [[Romagna]].{{sfn|Andenna|2014|p=76}} These emissaries insisted on the freeing and restoration of Guelphs.{{sfn|Andenna|2014|p=76}} When their peace efforts failed, the pope entrusted the bishops of Asti and Como to enforce the peace accords with the threat of excommunication and interdict.{{sfn|Andenna|2014|p=76}} In September, the pope appointed Aicardo Camodeia, a [[Franciscan]], as Archbishop of Milan.{{sfn|Andenna|2014|p=75}} During this time, the papal legate, Cardinal Bertrand du Poujet, proclaimed from Asti a holy [[Crusades|crusade]] against the Visconti.{{sfn|Beattie|2007|p=26}}

===Excommunication===
[[File:4886 - Milano - Loggia degli Osii - Foto Giovanni Dall'Orto, 23-Jan-2008.jpg|thumb|alt=A plaque on the Osii Loggia in Piazza Mercanti ("Merchant square") in Milan, built in 1316 by Scoto da San Gimignano for Matteo I Visconti|A plaque on the Osii Loggia in Piazza Mercanti ("Merchant square") in Milan, built in 1316 by Scoto da San Gimignano for Matteo I Visconti. Picture by Giovanni Dall'Orto]]

In 1322 at Avignon, Pope John XXII raised the charge of [[necromancy]] against Matteo.{{sfn|Russell|1972|p=194}} Matteo refused to appear before the court in the papal city, citing his age and the precarious state of health. The next month the court convicted Matteo ''[[trial in absentia|in absentia]]'' of necromancy.{{sfn|Law|1995|p=451}} In December, the Pope asked his appointee, the [[de jure]] Archbishop of Milan, Aicardo da Camodeia, to open a new case of heresy against Matteo and his son, [[Galeazzo I Visconti|Galeazzo]]. Archbishop Camodeia judged them as heretics, condemned Matteo, and ordered the confiscation of his property and the vacating of all his offices.{{sfn|Andenna|2014|p=77}}

At the end of May 1322, Matteo ceded power to his son Galeazzo and retired to [[Crescenzago]]. Matteo died on 24 June 1322.{{sfn|Armstrong|1932|p=[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.282060/page/n83 46]}}

==Family==
Matteo married [[Bonacossa Borri]]; they had:

*Floramonda, who married Guido Mandelli, the Count of [[Maccagno]];
*[[Galeazzo I Visconti|Galeazzo I]] (b. 1277), Lord of Milan, who married Beatrice d'[[House of Este|Este]],{{sfn|Peterson|2008|p=326}} daughter of [[Obizzo II d'Este]] and widow of [[Nino Visconti]];
*Beatrice (about n.1280), who married Spinetta Malaspina, Marquis of Verucola ([[Fivizzano]]);
*Catherine (b. about 1282), who married [[Alboino I della Scala]]{{sfn|Armstrong|1932|p=[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.282060/page/n63 26]}}
*[[Luchino Visconti (died 1349)|Luchino]] (b. about 1285) Lord of Milan,{{sfn|Lodge|1904|p=545}} married three times: to Violante of [[Margraves of Saluzzo|Saluzzo]], daughter of [[Thomas I of Saluzzo]], then to Caterina Spinola, daughter of Obizzo Spinola, and, in 1349, to Isabella [[Fieschi]], niece of [[Pope Adrian V]];{{sfn|Williams|1998|p=34}}
*[[Stefano Visconti|Stefano]] (b. about 1287),{{sfn|Lodge|1904|p=545}} Count of Arona, married Valentina [[Doria (family)|Doria]], daughter of Bernabò Doria and Eliana [[Fieschi family|Fieschi]];
*{{Interlanguage link|Marco I Visconti|it|3=Marco I Visconti|lt=Marco|vertical-align=sup}} (b. about 1289){{sfn|Black|2009|p=242}}
*[[Giovanni Visconti (archbishop)|Giovanni]] (b. about 1291), archbishop of Milan;{{sfn|Lodge|1904|p=545}}
*Zaccarina (b. around 1295), who married Otto Rusconi;
*Agnese, who married Cecchino [[Scaliger|della Scala]]

