The '''''Erzherzog Karl'' class''' was a class of [[pre-dreadnought battleship]]s of the [[Austro-Hungarian Navy]] built before [[World War I]]. All of the battleships of the ''Erzherzog Karl''-class were built in the [[Stabilimento Tecnico Triestino]] shipyards in [[Trieste]]. The first battleship, {{SMS|Erzherzog Karl||2}} was laid down in 1902. Construction on the remaining two battleships, {{SMS|Erzherzog Ferdinand Max|1905|2}} and {{SMS|Erzherzog Friedrich||2}} continued up to 1905.{{sfn|Hore|p=123}} ''Erzherzog Karl'' was commissioned in 1906, while ''Erzherzog Ferdinand Max'' and ''Erzherzog Friedrich'' were commissioned in 1907.{{sfn|Hore|p=123}} The three ''Erzherzog Karl''-class battleships were considered relatively modern by the time they were commissioned. However, small docking space and budget restraints resulted in the class being fairly compact. Nevertheless, they were well designed and properly protected.{{sfn|Hore|p=123}} The ''Erzherzog Karl'' class were the last and largest pre-dreadnoughts built by the Austrian Navy. They were named after senior members of the Austrian Imperial family.

Despite these qualities, the ''Erzherzog Karl''-class battleships were inferior to the [[Dreadnought]] type battleships (launched 1906) &nbsp;– with their "all big gun" armament and turbine propulsion. As a result, they only played a limited role during World War I.{{sfn|Hore|p=123}}  At the beginning of the war, the members of the ''Erzherzog Karl'' class formed the III division of the Austrian-Hungarian battle-fleet and were active in May 1915 in the combined fleet operation of bombardment of Italian ports and other vital communications. The battleships of the ''Erzherzog Karl'' class also participated in the flight of {{SMS|Goeben}} and {{SMS|Breslau}} during the opening days of the war.{{sfn|Hore|p=123}}

The ships also took part in suppressing a major mutiny among the crew members of two armoured cruisers stationed in [[Cattaro]] between 1–3&nbsp;February 1918.{{sfn|Halpern|pp=170–171}} Following Austria-Hungary's collapse in at the end of [[World War I]], ''Erzherzog Karl'' and ''Erzherzog Friedrich'' were handed over to France. The remaining battleship, ''Erzherzog Ferdinand Max'', was given to Great Britain. ''Erzherzog Karl'' ran aground at [[Bizerte]] and was broken up there in 1921. The remaining two battleships were scrapped in 1921 in Italy.{{sfn|Greger|p=23}}

== Design ==
=== General characteristics ===
[[File:Erzherzog-class.JPG|thumb|left|Right elevation and plan of the ''Erzherzog Karl'' class]]

The ''Erzherzog Karl'' class displaced {{convert|10472|LT|t|0}}. They were {{convert|414|ft|2|in|m|1}} long, had a [[Beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|71|ft|5|in|m|1}} and a [[Draught (hull)|draft]] of {{convert|24|ft|7|in|m|1}}. They were manned by 700 men.

=== Propulsion ===

The ships were propelled by two two-shaft, four cylinder [[Marine steam engine#Triple or multiple expansion|vertical triple expansion steam engines]]. Their designed speed was {{convert|19.3|kn|lk=in}},{{sfn|''R.U.S.I.''|1901|p=701}} but ''Erzherzog Karl'' developed {{convert|18000|ihp|0|lk=in|abbr=on}} on trials, achieving a speed of {{convert|20.5|kn|lk=in}}.{{sfn|Hore|p=123}}{{sfn|''R.U.S.I.''|1901|p=701}}

=== Armament ===
The ''Erzherzog Karl'' class carried a primary armament made by [[Škoda Works]].{{sfn|Hore|p=123}} On each ship, there were four [[Škoda 24 cm L/40 K97|{{convert|24|cm|1|sp=us|adj=on}}/40]] [[caliber]] guns in two twin turrets on the centerline. These guns were an Austro-Hungarian replica of the 24&nbsp;cm/40 (9.4") [[Krupp]] C/94, which was used on the ''Habsburg''s.{{sfn|Lienau (24 cm/40)}} The guns could be depressed to −5° and elevated to 30°.{{sfn|Lienau (24 cm/40)}} The [[arc of fire]] of the guns was 300°, or 150° in each direction.{{sfn|Lienau (24 cm/40)}} Each gun required a crew of twenty men.{{sfn|Lienau (24 cm/40)}} At maximum elevation, the gun could fire a {{convert|140|kg|lb|adj=on}} shell {{convert|16900|m|yd}}.{{sfn|Lienau (24 cm/40)}} or ten and a half miles. They could fire three to four armor-piercing shells per minute at a muzzle velocity of {{convert|690|m/s|ft/s}}. Each of the guns weighed at least {{convert|24040|kg|lb}}.{{sfn|Lienau (24 cm/40)}}

Their secondary armament consisted of twelve [[Škoda 19 cm Vz. 1904|{{convert|19|cm|1|abbr=on}}]]/42 caliber guns, also made by Škoda,{{sfn|Lienau (19 cm/42)}} mounted in eight single casemates on either wing of the ship and two single midships turrets on the either wing of the ship. They could be depressed to −3° and elevated to 20°.  They could fire a {{convert|97|kg|lb}} armor-piercing shell {{convert|20000|m|yd}} at maximum elevation with a muzzle velocity of {{convert|800|m/s|ft/s}}. The gun weighed 12.1 tons and could fire three rounds per minute.

The ships had a tertiary armament for protection against [[torpedo boats]] in the form of the [[Škoda 7 cm guns|{{convert|7|cm|in|abbr=on}}]]/45 caliber gun, too manufactured by Škoda.{{sfn|Lienau (7 cm/50)}} They could be depressed to −10° and elevated to 20, and had an arc of fire of 360°, meaning that they could fire at any target within their range of fire.{{sfn|Lienau (7 cm/50)}} The guns could fire about ten to fifteen rounds per minute.{{sfn|Lienau (7 cm/50)}} At their maximum elevation, the guns could fire a {{convert|4.5|kg|lb}} high-explosive charge {{convert|9140|m|yd}} at a muzzle velocity of {{convert|880|m/s|ft/s}}.{{sfn|Lienau (7 cm/50)}}

Anti-aircraft and airship protection was covered by the four {{convert|37|mm|adj=on|sp=us|1}} [[Vickers]] anti-aircraft guns on the ship.{{sfn|Lienau (.5-pdr)}} They could be depressed to −5° and elevated to 80°.  They had an arc of fire of 360°, which meant that they also could engage any target within their range.{{sfn|Lienau (.5-pdr)}} Manually operated by only one crewman,{{sfn|Lienau (.5-pdr)}} they could fire a {{convert|0.7|kg|lb}} shell {{convert|1830|m|yd}} at maximum elevation with a muzzle velocity of {{convert|640|m/s|ft/s}}.{{sfn|Lienau (.5-pdr)}} Designed in 1910, each of the guns weighed {{convert|57|kg|lb}}.{{sfn|Lienau (.5-pdr)}}  After 1916-17 refits two Škoda 7 cm L/45 guns on anti-aircraft mounts were installed.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Naval weapons of World War One|last=Friedman|first=Norman|date=2011-01-01|publisher=Seaforth|isbn=978-1848321007|oclc=786178793}}</ref> The ''Erzherzog Karl'' class was also fitted with two above water {{convert|45|cm|1|adj=on|sp=us}} [[torpedo tube]]s, although they were rarely used.{{sfn|Hore|p=123}}

=== Armor ===

The armor plating of the battleships around the waterline belt, one of the more vulnerable areas of a ship, was {{convert|210|mm|in|abbr=on|1}}, while their deck armor was {{convert|55|mm|in|abbr=on|1}}.{{sfn|Hore|p=123}} The turrets and casemates had {{convert|240|mm|in|abbr=on|1}} and {{convert|150|mm|in|abbr=on|1}} armor respectively. This was done in order to protect the battleships against a possible shell landing on the turrets and the imminent explosion resulting from such a hit.{{sfn|Hore|p=123}} The [[conning tower]] of the ships had {{convert|220|mm|in|abbr=on|1}} of armor plating, while the bulkheads inside the battleship that separated different compartments were {{convert|200|mm|in|abbr=on|1}} thick.{{sfn|Hore|p=123}}

== Construction ==

The ''Erzherzog Karl'' class, like the ''Habsburg'' class before them and the ''Radetzky'' class after them were named after archdukes of the Austro-Hungarian Royal Family, specifically [[Archduke Charles, Duke of Teschen]], [[Maximilian I of Mexico]] and [[Archduke Friedrich, Duke of Teschen]]. The ships were all laid down at the [[Stabilimento Tecnico Triestino]] in Trieste. The first ship of the class, {{SMS|Erzherzog Karl}} was laid down on 24 July 1902. Following 15 months of construction she was launched on 4 October 1903 and finally commissioned into the Austro-Hungarian Navy on 17 June 1906. The next ship of the class was {{SMS|Erzherzog Friedrich}}. She was laid down on 4 October 1902 and launched on 30 April 1904. ''Erzherzog Friedrich'' was finally commissioned into the Austro-Hungarian Navy on 31 January 1907. The third and final ship of the ''Erzherzog Karl'' class was {{SMS|Erzherzog Ferdinand Max|1905|6}}. She was laid down on 9 March 1904 and later launched on 21 May 1905. She was commissioned into the navy on 21 December 1907.{{sfn|Hore|p=123}}

