{{Islam}}
A [[fatwa]] ({{langx|ar|فتوى}}) is a non-binding legal opinion in [[Islam]], issued by an Islamically qualified religious law specialist, known as a ''[[mufti]]'', on a specific issue. The following is a list of notable historical and contemporary fatwas.

==Pre-19th century==
;1504 Oran fatwa
{{main|Oran fatwa}}
The [[Oran fatwa]] was issued in 1504 to address the crisis that occurred when Islam was prohibited in [[Crown of Castile|Castile]] in 1500{{ndash}}1502, and Muslims in the realm were [[Forced conversions of Muslims in Spain|required to convert]] and conform to Christianity.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=60}} The fatwa sets out detailed relaxations of the [[sharia]] (Islamic law) requirements, allowing the Muslims to conform outwardly to Christianity and perform acts that are ordinarily forbidden in Islamic law, if necessary to survive.{{sfn|Stewart|2007|p=266}} It includes relaxed instructions for fulfilling the [[salat|ritual prayers]], the [[zakat|ritual charity]], and the [[wudu|ritual ablution]], and recommendations when obliged to violate Islamic law, such as worshipping as Christians, committing [[Islam and blasphemy|blasphemy]], and consuming pork and wine.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|pp=61–62}} The fatwa enjoyed wide currency among Muslims and [[Morisco]]s (Muslims nominally converted to Christianity and their descendants) in [[History of Spain#Early Modern Spain|Spain]], but its influence was limited to that country.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=64}}
;1727 fatwa on non-religious books
Ruling by the Ottoman chief mufti solicited by the Ottoman ruler to lend religious legitimacy to the printing of nonreligious books.{{sfn|Dallal|Hendrickson|2009}}

==19th century==
;1803 fatwa against Western colonialism
Ruling by [[Shah Abdul Aziz]] in India invoking the legal theory obliging Muslims to wage war against the rulers of lands under European domination.{{sfn|Dallal|Hendrickson|2009}}
;1804 fatwa against Western colonialism
Ruling by [[Usman dan Fodio]] in West Africa invoking the legal theory obliging Muslims to wage war against the rulers of lands under European domination.{{sfn|Dallal|Hendrickson|2009}}
;1845 on vaccinations
Ruling by the Ottoman chief mufti solicited by the Ottoman ruler to lend religious legitimacy to vaccination.{{sfn|Dallal|Hendrickson|2009}}
;1891 fatwa against tobacco
Ruling by the Iranian [[Mirza Shirazi]] that prohibited smoking as long as the British tobacco monopoly was in effect, and led to the [[tobacco protest]].{{sfn|Dallal|Hendrickson|2009}}

==20th century==
;1904 fatwa against Western colonialism
Ruling by the Moroccan ulama on the obligation to dismiss of European experts hired by the Moroccan government.{{sfn|Dallal|Hendrickson|2009}}
;1907 fatwa against Western colonialism
Ruling by the Moroccan ulama on the obligation to depose the sultan on accusation that he failed to mount a defense against French aggression.{{sfn|Dallal|Hendrickson|2009}}
;1909 fatwa deposing Abdülhamid
When the [[Action Army]] entered Istanbul, a Fatwa was issued condemning [[Abdul Hamid II|Sultan Abdülhamid]], and the parliament voted to dethrone him.{{citation needed|date=May 2024}}
;1914 fatwa supporting Ottoman 'jihad' in World War I
Ruling by the Ottoman [[Shaykh al-Islam]] supporting the Ottoman sultan's proclamation of jihad to mark the entry of the Ottoman Empire into [[World War I]].{{sfn|Zürcher|2016|pp=14-18}}
;1922 fatwa deposing Sultan Vahideddin
[[Mehmed VI]] was deposed as Sultan of the Ottoman Empire and Caliph, on a fatwa from the commissar for religious affairs.<ref>{{cite web |title=Abolishment of the Caliphate by Mustafa Kemal and Its Effect on Indian Muslims|date=4 July 2021|url=https://turkvehint.org/2021/07/mohammed-ali/abolishment-of-the-caliphate-by-mustafa-kemal-and-its-effect-on-indian-muslims/|publisher=Türkiye ve Hindistan|access-date=12 November 2023}}</ref>
;1933 fatwa against Zionist products
Ruling by Iraqi ulama in 1933 calling on Muslims to boycott Zionist products.{{sfn|Dallal|Hendrickson|2009}}
;1947 fatwa calling for jihad on Zionism
On December 2, 1947, the University of Al-Azhar religious scholars, the most respected in the Sunni Muslim world, called for jihad against the Zionists.<ref>"Partition of Palestine and Declaration of Jihad", cited in Benny Morris, "1948 as Jihad", page 5.</ref>
;1951 fatwa on soft drinks
{{main|Coke Fatwa}}
In September 1951, the mufti of Egypt issued a fatwa stating that both Coca-Cola and Pepsi-Cola were permissible for Muslims to drink. In order to arrive at that decision, the Department of Fatwas had the Ministry of Public Health analyze the composition of the two drinks. As they did not find the pepsin or any narcotic or alcoholic substances to be present, nor any "microbes harmful to health", the mufti found that it was not forbidden under Islamic law.<ref name="Coke Fatwa">Liebesny, Herbert J., ''The law of the Near and Middle East readings, cases, and materials'', Albany: State University of New York Press, 1975, 42–43</ref>
;1959 fatwa on Jafari (Shia) jurisprudence
{{main|Al-Azhar Shia Fatwa}}
On July 6, 1959, Egypt's Sheikh [[Mahmud Shaltut|Shaltout]] issued the al-Azhar Shia fatwa opining that: "The [[Jaʽfari jurisprudence|Jafari]] [[fiqh]] of the [[Shi'a]] is a school of thought that is religiously correct to follow in worship as are other [[Sunni]] schools of thought."{{citation needed|date=June 2022}}
;1974 fatwa on the Ahmadiyyah community
In April 1974 the [[Muslim World League]] issued a fatwa stating that followers of the [[Ahmadiyyah]] movement are to be considered "non-Muslims".<ref>Yohanan Friedmann: Prophecy Continuous. Aspects of Ahmadi Religious Thought and Its Medieval Background. 2 Auflage. Oxford University Press, Neu-Delhi 2003, S. 44.</ref>
;1980 fatwa on singing
In 1980, the [[Grand Imam of al-Azhar]] [[Gad al-Haq|Gad al-Haq Ali Gad al-Haq]] issued a fatwa that "Listening to music, attending musical gatherings, and studying music of all genres and instruments is allowed as long as it is not accompanied with immoral and sinful acts, or used as a pretext to incite people towards haram (prohibited) behaviour, and it does not preoccupy a person away from observing the obligatory acts of worship (al-wajibat)".<ref name="IslamicTextInstitute">{{cite web |title=Fatwa on music by the Grand Mufti and Shaykh of Al-Azhar|date=26 April 2012|url=https://islamictextinstitute.co.za/music-azhar-fatwa/|publisher=Islamic Text Institute|access-date=13 October 2020}}</ref>
;1990s fatwa on nuclear weapons
{{main|Khamenei's fatwa against nuclear weapons}}
It refers to the [[fatwa]] against the acquisition, development and use of [[nuclear weapons]] by Ayatollah [[Ali Khamenei]].<ref name="AT">{{cite web|last=L Afrasiabi|first=Kaveh|url=http://www.atimes.com/atimes/Middle_East/HC17Ak02.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060316201913/http://www.atimes.com/atimes/Middle_East/HC17Ak02.html|url-status=unfit|archive-date=16 March 2006|title=An Iran option the US prefers to ignore|date=17 March 2006|work=[[Asia Times]]}}</ref> While the fatwa originally dates back to the mid-1990s,<ref name="foreign policy" /> the first public issue of it is reported to be that of October 2003, which was followed by an official statement at a meeting of the [[International Atomic Energy Agency]] (IAEA) in [[Vienna]], two years later in August 2005.

The fatwa has received criticism regarding its existence, applicability, and constancy.<ref name="Kessler-7-4-15">{{cite news|last1=Kessler|first1=Glenn|title=Fact Checker Did Iran's supreme leader issue a fatwa against the development of nuclear weapons?|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/fact-checker/wp/2013/11/27/did-irans-supreme-leader-issue-a-fatwa-against-the-development-of-nuclear-weapons/|access-date=7 April 2015|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=November 27, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403161326/http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/fact-checker/wp/2013/11/27/did-irans-supreme-leader-issue-a-fatwa-against-the-development-of-nuclear-weapons/|archive-date=2015-04-03|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Khalaji">{{citation|last1=Eisenstadt|first1=Michael|last2=Khalaji|first2=Mehdi|url=https://www.washingtoninstitute.org/uploads/Documents/pubs/PolicyFocus115.pdf|title=Nuclear Fatwa; Religion and Politics in Iran's Proliferation Strategy|publisher=[[Washington Institute for Near East Policy]]|date=September 2011|access-date=2015-08-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150428003851/http://www.washingtoninstitute.org/uploads/Documents/pubs/PolicyFocus115.pdf|archive-date=2015-04-28|url-status=live}}</ref> According to Khalaji, Khamenei may alter his fatwa under critical circumstances, in a similar manner as [[Khomeini]] did.<ref name="Khalaji"/> While, according to [[Gareth Porter]] in [[Foreign Policy]], Iran has sincerely banned the atomic bombs considering the "historical episode during its eight-year [[Iran–Iraq War|war with Iraq]]", when Iran never sought revenge for Iraqis chemical attacks killing 20,000 Iranians and severely injuring 100,000 more.<ref name="foreign policy">{{cite news|last=Porter|first=Gareth|author-link=Gareth Porter|title=When the Ayatollah Said No to Nukes|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2014/10/16/when-the-ayatollah-said-no-to-nukes/|access-date=21 August 2015|work=[[Foreign Policy]]|date=16 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170921001025/https://foreignpolicy.com/2014/10/16/when-the-ayatollah-said-no-to-nukes/|archive-date=2017-09-21|url-status=live}}</ref> Also, the fatwa is considered consistent with Islamic tradition.<ref name="Khalaji"/>
;1989 fatwa on Salman Rushdie
{{main|Fatwa on Salman Rushdie}}
One of the first well-known fatwas was proclaimed in 1989 by the [[Iran]]ian [[Ayatollah]] [[Ruhollah Khomeini]], against [[Salman Rushdie]] over his novel ''[[The Satanic Verses]]''.
;1992 fatwa on Farag Foda
In June 1992, Egyptian writer [[Farag Foda]] was assassinated following a fatwa issued by [[ulama]]s from [[Al-Azhar University|Al-Azhar]] who had adopted a previous fatwa by Sheikh al-Azhar, [[Gad al-Haq|Jadd al-Haqq]], accusing Foda and other secularist writers of being "enemies of Islam".<ref>{{cite book |last=Bar |first=Shmuel |title=Warrant for Terror: The Fatwas of Radical Islam and the Duty to Jihad |year=2008 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |page=16, footnote 8}}</ref> The jihadist group [[Al-Gama'a al-Islamiyya]] claimed responsibility for the murder.<ref name="deWaal">{{cite book |last=de Waal |first=Alex |author-link=Alex de Waal |title=Islamism and Its Enemies in the Horn of Africa |year=2004 |publisher=C. Hurst & Co |page=60}}</ref>
;1996 anti-American fatwa
{{main|Fatawā of Osama bin Laden#1996 fatwā}}
Issued by [[Osama bin Laden]] and [[Al-Qaeda]]. A 'Declaration of War against the Americans Occupying the Land of the Two Holy Places'.
;1998 anti-American fatwa
{{main|Fatawā of Osama bin Laden#1998 fatwā}}
Signed by the 'World Islamic Front for Jihad Against Jews and Crusaders' (Al-Qaeda). The five signatories were [[Osama bin Laden]], [[Ayman al-Zawahiri]], [[Ahmed Refai Taha]], [[Mir Hamzah]], and [[Fazlur Rehman Khalil|Fazlur Rehman]]. Decries America and Israel. Followed shortly after by the [[1998 United States embassy bombings]].
;1998 fatwa on Abdulaziz Sachedina
In 1998, Grand [[Ayatollah Sistani]] of [[Iraq]] issued a fatwā prohibiting [[University of Virginia]] professor [[Abdulaziz Sachedina]] from ever again teaching Islam due in part to Sachedina's writings encouraging acceptance of religious pluralism in the Muslim world.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uga.edu/islam/sachedina_silencing.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-02-23 |archive-date=2011-10-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111011121547/http://www.uga.edu/islam/sachedina_silencing.html |url-status=dead }}</ref>

==21st century==
===2000s===
;2004 fatwa against Israeli/US goods
[[Yusuf al-Qaradawi]] released a fatwā on April 14, 2004, stating that the boycott of American and Israeli products was an obligation for all who are able, in support of the Palestinian cause.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.islamonline.net/servlet/Satellite?pagename=IslamOnline-English-Ask_Scholar/FatwaE/FatwaE&cid=1119503543874 |title=Boycotting Israeli and American Goods – IslamonLine.net – Ask The Scholar |publisher=IslamonLine.net |date=2004-04-18 |access-date=2009-06-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090717080127/http://www.islamonline.net/servlet/Satellite?pagename=IslamOnline-English-Ask_Scholar%2FFatwaE%2FFatwaE&cid=1119503543874 |archive-date=2009-07-17 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.islamonline.net/servlet/Satellite?cid=1119503545220&pagename=IslamOnline-English-Ask_Scholar/FatwaE/FatwaEAskTheScholar |title=Ulama's Fatwa on Boycotting Israeli and American Products – IslamonLine.net – Ask The Scholar |publisher=IslamonLine.net |date=2003-06-30 |access-date=2009-06-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090717082116/http://www.islamonline.net/servlet/Satellite?cid=1119503545220&pagename=IslamOnline-English-Ask_Scholar%2FFatwaE%2FFatwaEAskTheScholar |archive-date=2009-07-17 }}</ref>
;2005 fatwa against al-Qaeda
[[Islam in Spain|Spanish Muslims]] proclaimed a fatwa against [[Osama bin Laden]] in March 2005<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culturekitchen.com/archives/002868.html |title=Text of the Fatwa Declared Against Osama Bin Laden by the Islamic Commission of Spain |access-date=2006-06-24 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050727013942/http://www.culturekitchen.com/archives/002868.html |archive-date=2005-07-27 }}</ref> issued by Mansur Escudero Bedate, Secretary General of the [[Islamic Commission of Spain]]. The ruling says that [[Osama bin Laden|Bin Laden]] and "his" [[al-Qaeda]] had [[apostacy|abandoned their religion]] and should thus be called "al-Qaeda terrorists" without using the [[adjective]] "Islamic". The fatwa urges other Muslims to make similar proclamations. They were followed in July 2005 by the [[Fiqh Council of North America]], a ruling council that issued a fatwa against providing support to "terrorist" groups that make up their own rules by unjustifiably referring to Islam (see [[Istihlal]]).
;2005 fatwa against religious pluralism, liberalism, and secularism
{{main|Fatwa on Religious Pluralism, Liberalism, and Secularism}}
;2005 Amman Message (fatwa against extremist ideology)
{{main|Amman Message}}
The Amman Message was a statement signed in 2005 in Jordan by nearly 200 prominent Islamic jurists to serve as a "counter-fatwa" against a widespread use of ''takfir'' (excommunication) by [[jihadist]] groups to justify jihad against rulers of Muslim-majority countries. The Amman Message recognized eight legitimate schools of Islamic law and prohibited declarations of apostasy against them. The statement also re-asserted that fatwas can be issued only by properly trained muftis.{{sfn|Dallal|Hendrickson|2009}}
;2007 fatwa on nuclear energy
In September 2007, the Central Java division and Jepara branch of the Indonesian organisation [[Nahdlatul Ulama]] (the Awakening of the Religious Scholars) declared the government's proposal to build a [[Nuclear power plant|nuclear power station]] nearby at Balong on the [[Mount Muria|Muria peninsula]] ''haram'' or forbidden. The fatwā was issued following a two-day meeting of more than a hundred ''ulama'' to consider the pros and cons of the proposal addressed by government ministers, scientists and critics. The decision cited both positive and negative aspects of the proposal, which it had balanced to make its judgment. Key concerns were the question of long-term safe disposal and storage of radioactive waste, the potential local and regional environmental consequences of the plant's operation, the lack of financial clarity about the project, and issues of foreign technological dependence.<ref>Richard Tanter, "Nuclear fatwa: Islamic jurisprudence and the Muria nuclear power station proposal", ''Austral Policy Forum'', 13 December 2007, 07-25A.</ref>
;2008 fatwa on smoking
In 2008, Syrian Grand Mufti Ahmad Badruddin Hassoun issued a fatwa prohibiting every type of smoking, including cigarettes and narghile, as well as the selling and buying of tobacco and any affiliation with tobacco distribution (see also [[smoking in Syria]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://islam.about.com/od/law/g/fatwa.htm |title=Islamic Glossary: Fatwa |publisher=Islam.about.com |date=2008-07-06 |access-date=2009-06-21}}</ref>
;2008 fatwa on President Asif Ali Zardari
In 2008, a Pakistani religious leader issued a fatwā on President [[Asif Ali Zardari]] for "indecent gestures" toward [[Sarah Palin]], U.S. vice presidential candidate.<ref>{{cite web|author=CJ: Rohini Verma |url=http://www.merinews.com/article/zardari-gets-fatwa-for-flirting-with-palin/143115.shtml |title=Zardari gets Fatwa for flirting with Palin |publisher=Merinews.com |access-date=2010-06-28}}</ref>
;2008 fatwa against terrorism
In 2008, Indian Ulama from the world-renowned seminary of Deoband have categorically issued a fatwā against terrorism and mentioned that any sort of killing of innocent people or civilians is ''[[haraam|haram]]'' (forbidden).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/2008/06/02/stories/2008060255231200.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080604100429/http://www.hindu.com/2008/06/02/stories/2008060255231200.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=2008-06-04 |title=Front Page News : Monday, June 28, 2010 |date= 2008-06-02|access-date=2010-06-28 |work=[[The Hindu]] |location=Chennai, India}}</ref> The fatwā also clarified that there is no jihad in Kashmir or against India as freedom of religion is guaranteed by the state as any state that guarantees freedom of religion cannot have jihad sanctioned against it.<ref>{{cite web|author=Not Specified |url=http://www.jammu-kashmir.com/archives/archives2008/kashmir20080228d.html |title=Deoband fatwa ruffles feathers of Kashmiri separatists |publisher=Jammu-kashmir.com |date=2008-02-28 |access-date=2010-06-28}}</ref> This fatwā was reiterated in 2009 where Indian Home Minister P. Chidrambram hailed the move.<ref>{{cite news|agency=TNN |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Chidambaram-reaches-out-seeks-Deoband-support-in-war-on-terrorism/articleshow/5193980.cms |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025072042/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-11-04/india/28104654_1_communalism-terrorism-fatwa |url-status=live |archive-date=2012-10-25 |title=Chidambaram reaches out, seeks Deoband support in war on terrorism |date=2009-11-04 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=2010-06-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mfsd.org/fatwaenglish.htm |title=Muslims for Secular Democracy |publisher=Mfsd.org |access-date=2010-06-28 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726004900/https://www.mfsd.org/fatwaenglish.htm |archive-date=2011-07-26 }}</ref>
;2009 Deoband fatwa against the Taliban
Deoband Ulama in India have repeatedly mentioned that the Taliban government in Afghanistan was un-Islamic. This was most recently reiterated at a convention in Karachi in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dawnnews.net/wps/wcm/connect/dawn-content-library/dawn/news/pakistan/12-deoband-ulema-term-all-taliban-actions-un-islamic--bi |title=Deoband ulema term all Taliban actions un-Islamic |publisher=Dawn News |date=2009-06-20 |access-date=2010-06-28 }} {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> These include the idea of establishing shariah rule with force in the name of Jihad and levying of ''jizya'' on Sikh citizens of Pakistan, which was termed as nothing more than extortion by armed gangs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/indian-clerics-flay-imposition-of-jizya-on/454905/ |title=Indian clerics flay imposition of 'Jizya' on Pakistani Sikhs |work=The Indian Express |date=2009-05-05 |access-date=2010-06-28}}</ref>

===2010s===
;2010 fatwa on singing
In June 2010, Shaikh [[Adil al-Kalbani]], former imam of the [[Masjid al-Haram|Grand Mosque in Makkah (Masjid al-Haram)]] issued a fatwa that "There is no clear-cut religious ruling that says singing and music are not permissible in Islam".<ref name="Gulf News">{{cite news |last= Shaheen|first= Abdul Rahman|date= 29 June 2010|title=Scholars divided over imam's fatwa on music|url=https://gulfnews.com/world/gulf/saudi/scholars-divided-over-imams-fatwa-on-music-1.647422| newspaper=Gulf News}}</ref>
;2010 Deoband fatwa against female employment
The [[Darul Uloom Deoband]] issued a fatwa "It is unlawful for Muslim women to do job in government or private enterprises where men and women work together and women have to talk to men frankly and without a veil". However, after an angry reaction from other clerics, the media and women's groups, it clarified that it only insists women must be "covered properly".<ref name="JSTOR">{{cite journal |date=22 May 2010|title=Deoband's Fatwas on Women|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/27807043| newspaper=JSTOR|jstor= 27807043|last1= Sikand|first1= Yoginder|volume= 45|issue= 21|pages= 15–17|publisher= Economic and Political Weekly}}</ref><ref name="TimesofIndia">{{cite news |last= Iqbal Siddiqui|first= Pervez|date=12 May 2010|title=Deoband fatwa: It's illegal for women to work, support family|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Deoband-fatwa-Its-illegal-for-women-to-work-support-family/articleshow/5919153.cms| newspaper=The Times of India}}</ref>
;2010 fatwa on Sunni-Shia relations
{{main|Fatwa of Ali Khamenei against insulting revered Sunni figures}}
On 30 September 2010, Ayatollah Ali Khamenei issued a fatwa against insulting revered Sunni figures following the insult of [[Aisha]] by [[Yasser Al-Habib]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hammond |first1=Andrew |title=Iran leader wins plaudits over sectarian strife fatwa |work=Reuters |date=13 October 2010 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/shiites-sunnis-khamenei-idAFLDE6930AA20101013 |access-date=2023-10-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190207020300/https://www.reuters.com/article/shiites-sunnis-khamenei-idAFLDE6930AA20101013 |archive-date=2019-02-07 |url-status=live }}</ref>
;2010 fatwa against terrorism and suicide bombings
{{main|Fatwa on Terrorism}}
The Fatwa on Terrorism is a 600-page Islamic decree against terrorism and [[suicide bombing]]s released in March 2010. This fatwa is a direct refutation of the ideology of [[Al-Qaeda]] and the [[Taliban]]. It is one of the most extensive rulings, an "absolute" condemnation of terrorism without "any excuses or pretexts" which goes further than ever and declares [[terrorism]] as [[kufr]] under [[Sharia|Islamic law]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Taylor |first=Jerome |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/sheikh-issues-fatwa-against-all-terrorists-1915000.html |title=Sheikh issues fatwa against all terrorists |work=The Independent |date=3 March 2010 |access-date=25 October 2011 |location=London |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110912181128/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/sheikh-issues-fatwa-against-all-terrorists-1915000.html |archive-date=2011-09-12 |url-status=live }}</ref> It was produced in [[Canada]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/influential-pakistani-cleric-based-in-gta-1.866827 |title=Influential Pakistani cleric based in GTA |publisher=CBC News |date=March 30, 2010 |access-date=October 25, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100402102656/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/influential-pakistani-cleric-based-in-gta-1.866827 |archive-date=2010-04-02 |url-status=live }}</ref> by an influential Muslim scholar Dr [[Muhammad Tahir-ul-Qadri]] and was launched in [[London]] on March 2, 2010. Dr Qadri said during the launch "Terrorism is terrorism, violence is violence and it has no place in Islamic teaching and no justification can be provided for it, or any kind of excuses or ifs or buts." According to [[CNN]], experts see the fatwa as a significant blow to terrorist recruiting.<ref>{{cite news |last=Khalid |first=Kiran |url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/asiapcf/03/03/terror.fatwa.analysis/index.html |title=Some experts see fatwa as significant blow to terrorist recruiting |publisher=CNN |date=March 3, 2010 |access-date=October 25, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108010752/http://www.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/asiapcf/03/03/terror.fatwa.analysis/index.html |archive-date=2012-11-08 |url-status=live }}</ref>
;2011 fatwa on Muammar al-Gaddafi
{{main|Killing of Muammar Gaddafi}}
In 2011, an Egyptian Muslim cleric, [[Yusuf al-Qaradawi]], issued a fatwa that urged soldiers to kill [[Muammar al-Gaddafi]], the leader of Libya, if they were able to do so.<ref name="NZ_Herald_10707969">{{cite news |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/world/news/article.cfm?c_id=2&objectid=10707969 |title='Shoot Gaddafi' fatwa issued |date=February 22, 2011 |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |access-date=October 15, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024210536/http://www.nzherald.co.nz/world/news/article.cfm?c_id=2&objectid=10707969 |archive-date=2012-10-24 |url-status=live }}</ref>
;2012 fatwa on the pyramids
In 2012, Sheikh Murgan Salem al-Gohary of Egypt, a former Taliban, issued a fatwa calling for "the destruction of the [[Great Sphinx of Giza|Sphinx]] and the [[Giza Pyramids]] in Egypt", because "God ordered Prophet Mohammed to destroy idols."<ref>{{cite news|title=Destroy the idols<!-- sic - no quotation marks --> Egyptian jihadist calls for removal of Sphinx, Pyramids|url=https://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/2012/11/12/Destroy-the-idols-Egyptian-jihadist-calls-for-removal-of-Sphinx-Pyramids.html|publisher=Al Arabiya|date=12 November 2012|access-date=28 June 2018}}</ref> 
;2012 Saudi fatwa on foreign media
In 2012, [[Abdul-Azeez ibn Abdullaah Aal ash-Shaikh]], the Grand Mufti of Saudi Arabia, issued a religious edict prohibiting contact and cooperation with foreign media outlets because they seek to "spread chaos and strife in Muslim lands". He added that contacting foreign media outlets to "divulge the country's secrets or address various matters" was tantamount to "treason and major crime". He said that "It is not permissible and is considered betrayal and assistance to the enemies of Islam." Also, "A believer has to help keeping security, that of his nation and community, and protecting his religion."<ref>{{cite web|title=Talking to foreign media is 'haram': Saudi Grand Mufti|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/articles/2012/11/11/248823.html|access-date=2012-11-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121115002057/http://english.alarabiya.net/articles/2012/11/11/248823.html|archive-date=2012-11-15|url-status=dead}}</ref>
;2012 fatwa on fasting under midnight sun
As the 2012 Ramadan fell under the northern summer, causing Muslims near or north of the [[Arctic Circle]] to be unable to eat for weeks, a fatwa by Dr. Abdullah Bin Abdul-Aziz Almosleh was implemented so that if the hours of sunlight exceeds 20 hours, Muslims could follow the time of [[Mecca]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Historisk ramadanavtale for nord-norske muslimer |url=https://www.utrop.no/nyheter/nytt/22898/ |trans-title=Historical Ramadan-agreement for north-norwegian muslims|language=nb|access-date=2025-01-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200805131558/https://www.utrop.no/nyheter/nytt/22898/ |archive-date=2020-08-05}}</ref>
;2012 Indonesian fatwa on Christmas greetings
In 2012, the [[Indonesian Ulema Council]] issued an edict for Muslims not to wish Christians a happy [[Christmas]]. The edict said that wishing a happy Christmas was akin to confirming the "misguided" teachings of Christianity.<ref>{{cite web|title=Christmas greetings chime despite edict |url=http://www2.thejakartapost.com/news/2012/12/26/christmas-greetings-chime-despite-edict.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160101011140/https://www2.thejakartapost.com/news/2012/12/26/christmas-greetings-chime-despite-edict.html |archive-date=2016-01-01 }}</ref>
;2013 fatwa on singing
In 2013, the grand mufti of Kashmir [[Bashir-ud-din Farooqi]] issued a fatwā terming singing as un-Islamic, forcing Kashmir's only all-girls rock band to abandon it.<ref>{{cite news|date=4 February 2013|title=A day after fatwa, Kashmir's all-girl band calls it quits|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/A-day-after-fatwa-Kashmirs-all-girl-band-calls-it-quits/articleshow/18331997.cms|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130211134640/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-02-04/india/36741962_1_rock-band-noma-nazir-online-threats|url-status=live|work=[[The Times of India]]|archive-date=11 February 2013}}</ref>
;2013 fatwa on Hamed Abdel-Samad
On 7 June 2013, Egyptian cleric and [[Al-Azhar University|Al-Azhar]] professor Mahmoud Shaaban accused [[Hamed Abdel-Samad]] of committing "heresy", and stated that "he must be killed for being a heretic ... if he refuses to recant" statements from his book and lectures on [[Islamic Fascism (book)|''Islamic Fascism'']]. Shaaban also stated that "after he has been confronted with the evidence, his killing is permitted if the [Egyptian] government does not do it." On the same day, the Egyptian Sheikh [[Assem Abdel Maged]] declared a fatwa against the publicist. The German Federal Government called on the Egyptian government to guarantee freedom of expression and personal safety and summoned the Egyptian Chargé d'Affaires in Berlin.<ref>{{Cite web |last=NACHRICHTEN |first=n-tv |title=Salafist ruft Fatwa gegen Deutschen aus |url=https://www.n-tv.de/politik/Salafist-ruft-Fatwa-gegen-Deutschen-aus-article10802466.html |access-date=2023-06-19 |website=n-tv.de |language=de}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=2013-06-09 |title=Mursi-Verbündeter: Mordaufruf gegen Publizist Abdel-Samad |language=de |work=Der Spiegel |url=https://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/mursi-verbuendeter-mordaufruf-gegen-publizist-abdel-samad-a-904619.html |access-date=2023-06-19 |issn=2195-1349}}</ref>
;2013 fatwa on terrorism and suicide bombings
On July 2, 2013, in [[Lahore]], 50 Muslim scholars of the Sunni Ittehad Council (SIC) issued a collective fatwa against suicide bombings, the killing of innocent people, bomb attacks, and targeted killings declaring them as ''haram'' or forbidden.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1022298 |title=Fatwa issued against suicide bombings, targeted killings and terrorism |date=2 July 2013 |location=Lahore}}</ref>
;2014 fatwa against illegal hunting and wildlife trade (Indonesia)
In March 2014 the [[Indonesian Council of Ulama]] (Indonesia's highest Islamic clerical body) issued a fatwa against illegal hunting and wildlife trafficking. The fatwa instructed Muslims to protect [[endangered species]] by conserving their habitat and stopping illegal trade. The [[World Wide Fund for Nature]] described the fatwa as a positive step.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-26452346|title=Muslim clerics ban illegal hunting and wildlife trade|work=[[BBC News]]|date=2014-03-05|access-date=2018-06-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170806044120/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-26452346|archive-date=2017-08-06|url-status=live}}</ref>
;2014 fatwa against ISIS
{{Main|Fatwa of Sheikh Abubakr Ahmad on ISIS}}
On August 27, 2014, [[Sheikh Abubakr Ahmad]], the current [[Grand Mufti of India]] is issued the first<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khaleejtimes.com/international/india/fight-terror-with-education|title=Fight terror with education|last=Kumar|first=Ashwani|website=Khaleej Times|language=en|access-date=15 February 2020|quote=Education is the most powerful weapon in the fight against terrorism and also the best medicine against all social ills, feels Sheikh Aboobacker Ahmed, religious Muslim leader in India who is also the first scholar to issue a fatwa against the terror group [[Daesh]].}}</ref> fatwa against ISIS.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Muslim-cleric-in-Kerala-issues-fatwa-against-ISIS-jihadists-sell-several-dozens-of-Yazidi-women/articleshow/41281217.cms|title=Muslim cleric in Kerala issues fatwa against ISIS; jihadists sell several dozens of Yazidi women {{!}} India News - Times of India|date=30 August 2014|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=15 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Wasserstein|first=David J.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TDYuDwAAQBAJ&q=%22fatwa%22&pg=PA204|title=Black Banners of ISIS: The Roots of the New Caliphate|date=22 August 2017|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=978-0-300-23143-4|language=en}}</ref>
;2015 fatwa against terrorism
In December 2015, about 70,000 clerics of [[Bareilly Sharif Dargah|Dargah Aala Hazrat]] in India issued a fatwa against terrorism and terrorist organizations like ISIS, Taliban and Al Qaeda and said these organization were not Islamic organizations.<ref name="TOI1">{{cite news |date= 9 December 2015|title=70,000 clerics issue fatwa against terrorism, 15 lakh Muslims support it|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/70000-clerics-issue-fatwa-against-terrorism-15-lakh-Muslims-support-it/articleshow/50100656.cms| newspaper=The Times of India}}</ref>
;2015 fatwa against ISIS
On March 11, 2015, [[Syed Soharwardy]], the founder of the [[Islamic Supreme Council of Canada]], and 37 other Muslim leaders of various Islamic sects from across Canada gathered in [[Calgary]] and issued a fatwa condemning followers of the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State (ISIS)]] as non-Muslims. Soharwardy cited capturing opponents and beheading them, killing Muslims who disagree with ISIS's actions, destroying mosques, burning enemy soldiers alive and encouraging Muslim girls to join ISIS, among others, as acts by ISIS that violate Islamic law. Under this fatwa, anybody who even wishes to join the group will be "excommunicated from the Muslim community" and no longer considered Muslim.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ca.news.yahoo.com/canadian-imams-issue-fatwa-isil-supporters-calling-them-183339522.html |title=Canadian Press story about Calgary fatwa |access-date=2015-03-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402143620/https://ca.news.yahoo.com/canadian-imams-issue-fatwa-isil-supporters-calling-them-183339522.html |archive-date=2015-04-02 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.islamicsupremecouncil.com/resources/historic-islamic-edict-fatwa-on-joining-isis-isil/ |title=ISCC's announcement of fatwa against ISIS |access-date=2015-03-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150312160925/http://www.islamicsupremecouncil.com/resources/historic-islamic-edict-fatwa-on-joining-isis-isil/ |archive-date=2015-03-12 |url-status=live }}</ref>
;2016 Fatwa of Peace for Humanity
{{Main|Fatwa of Peace for Humanity}}
;2017 fatwa on suicide bombings
In 2017, suicide bombing in any form has also been declared ''haram'' by Indian ulama.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Muslim-clerics-denounce-Taliban-threat/articleshow/5133316.cms | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025072050/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2009-10-17/india/28110543_1_taliban-threat-clerics-hakimullah-mehsud | url-status=live | archive-date=2012-10-25 | first1=Mohammed | last1=Wajihuddin | work=[[The Times of India]] | title=Muslim clerics denounce Taliban threat | date=2009-10-17}}</ref> This stand is also supported by Saudi scholars such as Shaykh [[Muhammad ibn al-Uthaymeen|Muhammad Bin Saalih al-'Uthaymeen]], who have issued fatwā declaring suicide bombings are ''haram'' and those who commit this act are not ''shaheed'' (martyrs).<ref>Shaykh Muhammad Bin Saalih al-'Uthaymeen</ref>
;2018 fatwa against MMR vaccine (Indonesia)
In August 2018, The [[Indonesian Ulema Council]] issued a fatwa declaring the [[MMR vaccine|MMR (Measles, Mumps and Rubella) vaccine]] as haram, and claimed the vaccine contains traces of pork and human cells.<ref name="ABC News">{{cite news |last= Wibawa|first= Tasha|date= 21 August 2018|title=Indonesia's top Islamic body issues fatwa against measles vaccine, calling it 'religiously forbidden'|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-08-21/indonesia-vaccines-measles-fatwa-issued-by-mui/10147040| newspaper=ABC News}}</ref><ref name="CIDRAP">{{cite web |date= 11 September 2020|title=Rising vaccine wariness in some nations doesn't bode well for COVID vaccines|url=https://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2020/09/rising-vaccine-wariness-some-nations-doesnt-bode-well-covid-vaccines|publisher=Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy|access-date=11 October 2020}}</ref>

===2020s===
;2020 fatwa against visiting Al-Aqsa Mosque via 'normalized' aviation routes
The Palestinian Authority's Grand Mufti issued a fatwa banning Muslims from visiting al-Aqsa Mosque having arrived through Israeli airports by means of aviation agreements signed within the context of 'normalization' deals between Israel and Arab Gulf states.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.jpost.com/arab-israeli-conflict/pas-grand-mufti-issues-fatwa-banning-muslims-from-praying-at-al-aqsa-639265 | title=PA's Grand Mufti issues fatwa banning Muslims from praying at al-Aqsa | date=20 August 2020 }}</ref>
;2020 fatwa against normalization with Israel (Sudan)
Sudan's Islamic Fiqh Council, the country's highest religious authority, issued a fatwa against normalization with Israel.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2020/10/321423/sudan-religious-authorities-issue-fatwa-against-israel-normalization | title=Sudan Religious Authorities Issue Fatwa Against Israel Normalization }}</ref>
;2021 fatwa against normalization with Israel, call for jihad (Mauritania)
A fatwa signed by over 200 Mauritanian Muslim clerics called normalization with Israel 'A Betrayal Of Allah, His Messenger And The Muslims' and that jihad against Israel was a religious duty.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.memri.org/reports/fatwa-signed-over-200-mauritanian-muslim-clerics-normalization-israel-betrayal-allah-his | title=Fatwa Signed by over 200 Mauritanian Muslim Clerics: Normalization with Israel is 'A Betrayal of Allah, His Messenger and the Muslims'; Jihad Against Israel is a Religious Duty }}</ref>
;2022 fatwa against homosexuality (South Africa)
In July 2022, the South African [[Muslim Judicial Council]] (MJC) issued a fatwa on homosexuality. The fatwa clarified that Islam's primary sources of legislation are the Qur’an, Sunnah and Ijma – or scholarly consensus – all of which "unequivocally prohibit same-sex actions and, by extension, same-sex marriage".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.vocfm.co.za/mjc-releases-fatwa-on-homosexuality/ | title=MJC releases fatwa on homosexuality – Voice of the Cape | date=5 July 2022 }}</ref>
;2023 fatwa calling for military intervention by Arab and Muslim countries against Israel and for Gaza (Qatar)
On October 31, 2023, [[International Union of Muslim Scholars|The International Union of Muslim Scholars (IUMS)]], in a fatwa, urged all [[Arabs|Arab]] and [[Muslims|Muslim]] nations to support [[Hamas]] in its military campaign against [[Israel]], as well as the Palestinian resistance groups in the [[West Bank]] and Israel, as well as the nations that border Israel, such as [[Egypt]], [[Jordan]], [[Syria]], and [[Lebanon]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.memri.org/reports/qatar-based-and-funded-international-union-muslim-scholars-iums-issues-fatwa-calling#_edn1 | title=Qatar-Based And -Funded International Union Of Muslim Scholars (IUMS) Issues Fatwa Calling For Military Intervention By Arab And Muslim Countries Against Israel And For Gaza }}</ref>
;2023 fatwa boycotting Israel-linked firms (Indonesia)
On November 10, 2023, a fatwa issued by the [[Indonesian Ulema Council]] called for the boycott of pro-Israel goods as a show of support to Palestine.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.barrons.com/news/indonesian-clerics-issue-fatwa-boycotting-israel-linked-firms-822c9d7b | title=Indonesian Clerics Issue Fatwa Boycotting Israel-linked Firms }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/indonesia/2023/11/10/mui-calls-for-israeli-goods-boycott-issues-fatwa-in-support-of-palestine.html | title=MUI calls for Israeli goods boycott, issues fatwa in support of Palestine - Society }}</ref>

;2023 fatwa for Gazans against Israel (Turkey)
On November 16, 2023, Turkey's governmental [[Directorate of Religious Affairs]] muftis meeting issued a 10-item declaration<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-11-16 |title=43. İl Müftüleri İstişare Toplantısı Sonuç Bildirgesi yayımlandı |trans-title=The Final Declaration of the 43rd Provincial Muftis Consultation Meeting has been published |url=https://www.diyanet.gov.tr/tr-TR/Kurumsal/Detay/35982/43-il-muftuleri-istisare-toplantisi-sonuc-bildirgesi-yayimlandi |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231123053254/https://www.diyanet.gov.tr/tr-TR/Kurumsal/Detay/35982/43-il-muftuleri-istisare-toplantisi-sonuc-bildirgesi-yayimlandi |archive-date=2023-11-23 |access-date=2023-11-23 |website=[[Directorate of Religious Affairs]] |language=tr}}</ref> forbidding Muslims to support Israel: "Remaining indifferent to oppression and injustice, staying silent in the face of tyrants and traitors, is directly or indirectly supporting oppressors, occupiers, terrorists and killers. Supporting those who support them is also forbidden."<ref>{{Cite web |last=Bozkurt |first=Abdullah |date=2023-11-22 |title=Turkey's Diyanet religious directorate stands firm with Hamas, issues anti-Israel fatwa |url=https://nordicmonitor.com/2023/11/turkeys-religious-directorate-diyanet-stands-firm-with-hamas-issues-anti-israel-fatwa/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231122045115/https://nordicmonitor.com/2023/11/turkeys-religious-directorate-diyanet-stands-firm-with-hamas-issues-anti-israel-fatwa/ |archive-date=2023-11-22 |access-date=2023-11-23 |website=[[Nordic Monitor]] |language=en-US}}</ref> The directorate's president earlier on November 13 said "Millions taking to the streets for Gaza and Palestine are an intifada of humanity against brutal Zionism."<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-11-13 |title=Gazze, Filistin için sokaklara dökülen milyonlar vahşi Siyonizm'e karşı insanlığın bir intifadasıdır |trans-title=Millions taking to the streets for Gaza and Palestine are an intifada of humanity against brutal Zionism. |url=https://www.diyanet.gov.tr/tr-TR/Kurumsal/Detay/35973/gazze-filistin-icin-sokaklara-dokulen-milyonlar-vahsi-siyonizme-karsi-insanligin-bir-intifadasidir |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231123053759/https://www.diyanet.gov.tr/tr-TR/Kurumsal/Detay/35973/gazze-filistin-icin-sokaklara-dokulen-milyonlar-vahsi-siyonizme-karsi-insanligin-bir-intifadasidir |archive-date=2023-11-23 |access-date=2023-11-23 |website=[[Directorate of Religious Affairs]] |language=tr}}</ref>

;2025 fatwa of jihad against Israel

On 28 March 2025, scholars from the [[International Union of Muslim Scholars]] issued a fatwa that stated, "jihad against the [Israeli] occupation is an individual obligation upon every capable Muslim" while calling upon every Muslim government to "intervene immediately" through military, economic and political means. In response, the [[Dar al-Ifta al-Misriyyah|Grand Mufti of Egypt]], Nazir Ayyad, rejected the fatwa and called the action "irresponsible". He added that such actions may "endanger the security of societies and the stability of Muslim states."<ref>{{cite web|title= What to do?: 'jihad against Israel' fatwa pits IUMS against Egypt's top religious authority Dar al-Ifta|url= https://www.newarab.com/news/jihad-israel-fatwa-pits-iums-against-egypts-dar-al-ifta|website= The New Arab|date=10 April 2025}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Egypt's grand mufti rejects fatwa for jihad against Israel as 'irresponsible'|url= https://www.middleeasteye.net/news/egypts-mufti-opposes-calls-armed-jihad-against-israel|website=Middle East Eye|date=8 April 2025}}</ref>

