'''Michel Aflaq''' ({{langx|ar|ميشيل عفلق|Mīšīl ʿAflaq}}&lrm;, {{IPA|ar|miˈʃel ˈʕaflaq}}; 9 January 1910 – 23 June 1989) was a Syrian philosopher, [[sociology|sociologist]] and [[Arab nationalism|Arab nationalist]]. His ideas played a significant role in the development of [[Ba'athism]] and its political movement; he is considered by several Ba'athists to be the principal founder of Ba'athist thought. Aflaq published various books during his lifetime, such as ''The Road to Renaissance'' (1940), ''The Battle for One Destiny'' (1958) and ''The Struggle Against Distorting the Movement of Arab Revolution'' (1975).

Born into a middle-class family in [[Damascus]], Syria, he studied at the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]], where he met his future political companion [[Salah al-Din al-Bitar]]. Aflaq returned to Syria (at that time part of the French-ruled [[Mandate for Syria and the Lebanon]]) in 1932, beginning his political career in [[Communism|communist politics]]. He became a communist activist, but broke his ties with the communist movement when the [[Syrian–Lebanese Communist Party]] supported colonial policies through the [[Popular Front (France)|Popular Front]] under the [[French Mandate of Syria]]. In 1940, Aflaq and al-Bitar established the [[Arab Ihya Movement]] (later renaming itself the ''Arab Ba'ath Movement'', taking the name from [[Zaki al-Arsuzi]]'s group by the [[Arab Ba'ath|same name]]). The movement proved successful, and in 1947 the Arab Ba'ath Movement merged with al-Arsuzi's Arab Ba'ath organisation to establish the [[Ba'ath Party|Arab Ba'ath Party]]. Aflaq was elected to the party's executive committee and was elected "'Amid" (meaning the party's leader).

The Arab Ba'ath Party merged with [[Akram al-Hawrani]]'s [[Arab Socialist Party]] to establish the Arab Socialist Ba'ath Party in 1952; Aflaq was elected the party's leader in 1954. During the mid-to-late 1950s the party began developing relations with [[Gamal Abdel Nasser]], the [[President of Egypt]], which eventually led to the establishment of the [[United Arab Republic]] (UAR). Nasser forced Aflaq to dissolve the party, which he did, but without consulting with party members. Shortly after the UAR's dissolution, Aflaq was reelected as Secretary General of the National Command of the Ba'ath Party. Following the [[8th of March Revolution]], Aflaq's position within the party was weakened to such an extent that he was forced to resign as the party's leader in 1965. Aflaq was ousted during the [[1966 Syrian coup d'état]], which led to a schism within the Ba'ath Party. He escaped to [[Lebanon]], but later went to Iraq. In 1968 Aflaq was elected Secretary General of the [[Ba'ath Party (Iraqi-led faction)|Iraqi-led Ba'ath Party]]; during his tenure he held no ''de facto'' power. He held the post until his death on 23 June 1989.

Aflaq's theories about society, economics, and politics, which are collectively known as Ba'athism, hold that the [[Arab world]] needs to be unified into one [[Arab Nation]] in order to achieve an advanced state of development. He was critical of both capitalism and communism, and critical of [[Karl Marx]]'s view of [[dialectical materialism]] as the only truth. Ba'athist thought placed much emphasis on liberty and [[Arab socialism]] – a socialism with Arab characteristics, which was not part of the international socialist movement as defined by the West. Aflaq believed in the separation of state and religion, and was a strong believer in [[Secularization|secularisation]], but was against [[atheism]]. Although a Christian, he believed [[Islam]] to be proof of "Arab genius". In the aftermath of the 1966 Ba'ath Party split, the [[Ba'ath Party (Syrian-dominated faction)|Syrian-led Ba'ath Party]] accused Aflaq of stealing al-Arsuzi's ideas, calling him a "thief" and later sentenced him to "death ''via absentia''" in 1971.{{Efn|Sources:
* {{cite book |author=Tucker, Spencer |title=The Encyclopedia of Middle East Wars: The United States in the Persian Gulf, Afghanistan, and Iraq Conflicts |volume=1 |publisher=[[ABC-CLIO]] |year=2010 |isbn=978-1851099474|pages=29, 30|chapter=Aflaq, Michel}}
* {{Cite book |last=Cragg |first=Kenneth |title=The Arab Christian: A History in the Middle East |publisher=Westminster John Knox Press |year=1991 |isbn=0-664-22182-3 |edition=1st |location=Louisville, Kentucky, USA |pages=162 |chapter=7: Modern Arabs and the Intentions of Arabism}}
* {{Cite book |last=A. Shoup |first=John |title=The History of Syria |publisher=ABC-CLIO, LLC |year=2018 |isbn=978-1-4408-5834-5 |location=Santa Barbara, California |pages=151, 152 |chapter=Notable People in the History of Syria |lccn=2018020377}}
* {{Cite book |last=Tibi |first=Bassam |title=Arab Nationalism: Between Islam and the Nation-State |publisher=Macmillan Press Ltd |year=1997 |isbn=978-0-333-63647-3 |edition=3rd |location=London, UK |pages=205 |chapter=11: Pan-Arab Nationalism as Westernised ideology and politics of Arab States: Between Ba'thism and Nasserism until the Six-Day War}}
* {{Cite book |last=Dwyer |first=Kevin |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qajOCwAAQBAJ&dq=Aflaq+condemned+to+death+by+absentia&pg=PT214 |title=Arab Voices: The human rights debate in the Middle East |publisher=Routledge |year=2016 |isbn=978-1-138-19070-2 |location=New York, NY}}
* {{Cite book |last=Roberts |first=David |title=The Ba'ath and the creation of modern Syria |publisher=Routledge |year=2015 |isbn=978-0-415-83882-5 |edition=Routledge Library Editions: Syria |location=Abingdon, Oxon |pages=103 |chapter=11: Hafiz al-Asad - I |quote=}}}} The [[Ba'ath Party (Iraqi-dominated faction)|Iraqi-led Ba'ath Party]] rejects this, and does not believe that al-Arsuzi contributed to Ba'athist thought.

== Early life ==
Aflaq was born on 9 January 1910 to a middle-class [[Eastern Orthodoxy in Syria|Orthodox Christian]] family in [[Damascus]]{{sfn|Helms|1984|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=JQ6jPM38qCwC&pg=PA64 64–65]}} where his father Joseph worked as a [[Grain trade|grain merchant]]. He was first educated in the Westernised schools of the French-ruled [[Mandate for Syria and the Lebanon]].{{sfn|Salem|1994|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=KZru-kaTZCcC&pg=PA61 61]}} In 1929, he left Syria to study philosophy at the [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]] in Paris; during his stay, he was influenced by the works of [[Henri Bergson]] and met his longtime collaborator [[Salah al-Din al-Bitar]], a fellow Syrian nationalist.{{sfn|Benewick|Green|1988|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=qJrCWS4TU1sC&pg=PA4 4]}} Aflaq founded an Arab Student Union at the Sorbonne and discovered the writings of [[Karl Marx]]. He returned to Syria in 1932, and became active in communist politics, but left the movement when the government of [[Léon Blum]], supported by the [[French Communist Party]] (PCF), continued France's old policies towards its colonies. Aflaq and others had believed that the PCF had a pro-independence attitude towards the [[French colonies]]. It did not help that the [[Syrian–Lebanese Communist Party]] (SLCP) supported the PCF's decision. From then on, Aflaq saw the communist movement as a tool of the [[Soviet Union]].{{sfn|Ali|2003|p=[https://archive.org/details/clashoffundament00alit/page/110 110]}} He was impressed by the organisation and ideology of [[Antun Saadeh]]'s [[Syrian Social Nationalist Party]].{{sfn|Salem|1994|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=KZru-kaTZCcC&pg=PA61 61]}}

== Political career ==

=== Arab Ba'ath Movement: 1940–1947 ===
[[File:Baath Party founder Michel Aflaq in the late 1930s.jpg|thumb|Aflaq in the late 1930s]]
Upon their return to Syria, Aflaq and al-Bitar became teachers at Tajhiz all'-Ula, "the most prestigious secondary school in Syria".{{Citation needed|date=January 2026}} Aflaq taught history, while al-Bitar taught math and physics. By 1940, Aflaq and al-Bitar had set up a student circle, which usually met on Fridays. That year, the [[Arab Ba'ath Movement|Arab Ihya Movement]], a political party, was established by Aflaq and al-Bitar. They used most of their spare time in 1941 to agitate for the party. It was in 1942 that Aflaq showed his skills as "a compelling speaker" who was able to utilize the "theatrical pause" to great effect.{{sfn|Seale|1990|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6D9EiJKRTHcC&pg=PA29 29]}} The party changed its name to ''Arab Ba'ath Movement'' to signify the radical changes which were sweeping the Middle East; [[Rashid Ali al-Gaylani]], the [[Prime Minister of Iraq]], had challenged Britain's domination over Iraq. The replacement of the word "Revival" with "Ba'ath" ({{langx|ar|بعث}}, literally means ''resurrection''/''rebirth'') signified that Arab revival had been replaced ideologically by the need for an Arab rebirth. The change of name led [[Zaki al-Arsuzi]], leader of the [[Arab Ba'ath Party]], to accuse Aflaq and al-Bitar of stealing his party's name from him. Though both men were promoting a party platform based on an [[Arab nationalist]] stance, Aflaq and al-Arsuzi became bitter rivals.{{sfn|Seale|1990|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6D9EiJKRTHcC&pg=PA30 30]}}

On 24 October 1942, both Aflaq and al-Bitar resigned from their teaching positions, now determined to devote themselves fully to the political struggle.{{sfn|Seale|1990|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6D9EiJKRTHcC&pg=PA29 29]}} In 1941 the [[Syrian Committee to Help Iraq]] was established to support the Iraqi Government led by Rashid Ali al-Gaylani against the British invasion during the [[Anglo–Iraqi War]].{{sfn|Tucker|2010|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=U05OvsOPeKMC&pg=PA30 30]}} Al-Arsuzi, the leader of the other Arab Ba'ath movement, was skeptical of the new committee, and opposed helping the Iraqis on the ground that they would lose anyway.{{sfn|Curtis | 1971|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=1zxOruujp_IC&pg=PA139 139]}} In 1941 the movement began publishing documents under the name the "Arab Ihya Movement". Later, in 1945, Aflaq and al-Bitar asked the French Mandate authorities to grant the movement a party license. The Arab Ba'ath Movement did not become an official party until 1947, when it merged with al-Arsuzi's Arab Ba'ath Movement to found the [[Ba'ath Party|Arab Ba'ath Party]].{{sfn|Rabil|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=M18Jj0bMMl0C&pg=PA17 17]}} The Arab Ba'ath Movement, led by Aflaq and al-Bitar, drew supporters from al-Arsuzi's Ba'ath Movement; during the 1940s, al-Arsuzi started to seclude himself from the public eye; he developed a deep distrust of others and became, according to some of his associates, [[paranoid]].{{sfn|Curtis|1971|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=1zxOruujp_IC&pg=PA138 138–139]}} When the two Ba'ath movements merged and established the Arab Ba'ath Party in 1947, the only subject discussed was how much socialism to include; [[Wahib al-Ghanim]] and [[Jalal al-Sayyid]] from the al-Arsuzi-led Ba'ath movement wanted Aflaq and al-Bitar to adopt more radical socialist policies.{{sfn|Seale|1990|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6D9EiJKRTHcC&pg=PA34 34]}}{{Failed verification|date=December 2024}}

=== Founding and early years ===
The Arab Ba'ath Party's first congress was held in Damascus in 1947.{{sfn|Rabinovich|1972|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=IL-A_YxL2m4C&pg=PA228 228]}} Aflaq took the pre-eminent position of ''Amid'' (sometimes translated as 'doyen' or as 'leader'){{sfn|Jabel|1966|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=Ix2NAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Aflaq%22+amid 31]}} and was elected to a four-member executive committee. Under the constitution adopted at the congress, this made him effective leader of the party, with sweeping powers within the organisation. Al-Bitar was elected Secretary General of the National Command. Zaki al-Arsuzi, the leader of the Arab Ba'ath, was not given any position or membership in the party.{{sfn|Seale|1990|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6D9EiJKRTHcC&pg=PA34 34]}} As ''Amid'', Aflaq was responsible for ideological affairs and became the party's mentor, while al-Bitar controlled the party's day-to-day management.{{sfn|Moubayed|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=sC-xU8QHSooC&pg=PA131 131]}} The merger would prove problematic; several members of the al-Arsuzi-led Ba'ath Party were more left-leaning, and would become, later in Aflaq's tenure, highly critical of his leadership.{{sfn|Abdulghani|1984|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=AgMOAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA27 27]}}
[[File:Michel Aflaq and other Ba"ath Party leaders returned Syria after dictator Adib Shishakli fleed the country, 1954.jpg|thumb|Aflaq and other Ba'ath Party leaders in 1954]]
In the late 1940s, Aflaq and al-Bitar gave free lessons on Ba'athist thought, and in 1948 established the newspaper ''[[al-Ba'ath]]''. Aflaq tested the Ba'ath Party's strength during the [[1948 Arab–Israeli War]]: after early Syrian defeats, he led several demonstrations against the government led by President [[Shukri al-Quwatli]]. He personally led demonstrations and claimed that al-Quwatli, a [[landowner]], was a corrupt and capitalistic politician, who was to blame for the Syrian army's defeat. Aflaq called for al-Quwatli's resignation, and wrote several ''al-Ba'ath'' articles criticising his presidency and his prime minister, [[Jamil Mardam Bey]],{{sfn|Moubayed|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=sC-xU8QHSooC&pg=PA131 131]}} who later had Aflaq arrested.{{sfn|Moubayed|2006|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=sC-xU8QHSooC&pg=PA131 131–132]}} Al-Quwatli's government was brought down in a coup d'état led by military officer [[Husni al-Za'im]]. Al-Za'im banned all parties, claiming that Syria was not ready to establish a [[liberal democracy]]. Aflaq, who had been set free, was rearrested during al-Zai'm's presidency and sent to the notorious [[Mezzeh Prison]]. Al-Za'im's rule did not last for long, and in August 1949, he was toppled, and [[Hashim al-Atassi]], who was democratically elected, took his place. Al-Atassi established a [[national unity government]], and Aflaq was appointed to the post of [[Ministry of Education (Syria)|Minister of Education]], the only government post he would ever hold; he held it from August to December 1949. Al-Attasi's presidency did not last for very long either, and in 1951 [[Adib Shishakli]] took power in a military coup.{{sfn|Moubayed|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=sC-xU8QHSooC&pg=PA132 132]}}

Aflaq at first extended his support to the new government, believing that he and the Ba'ath Party could collaborate with Shishakli because they shared the same Arab nationalist sentiments. His analysis of Shishakli proved to be wrong, and one of Shishakli's first decisions as ruler was to ban all political parties, including Aflaq's.{{sfn|Moubayed|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=sC-xU8QHSooC&pg=PA132 132]}} The Ba'ath Party leadership, and several leading members, escaped to Lebanon in the wake of increased government repression. In Lebanon Aflaq and al-Bitar agreed to a merger of the Arab Ba'ath Party and the [[Arab Socialist Party]] (ASP), led by [[Akram al-Hawrani]], to establish the Arab Socialist Ba'ath Party in 1952.{{sfn|George|2003|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=dFdbVVcKsSIC&pg=PA66 66–67]}} The newly formed party worked as a base of operation against Shishakli's rule. Aflaq and the rest cooperated with non-Ba'athist opposition forces too. Shishakli was toppled in February 1954.{{sfn|Moubayed|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=sC-xU8QHSooC&pg=PA132 132]}}

=== Power politics: 1954–1963 ===
[[File:Leaders of July 14 1958 Revolution.jpg|thumb|left|Aflaq (front row, first from right) with the leaders of the [[14 July Revolution|14 July 1958 revolution]] in Iraq, including [[Khaled al-Naqshabendi]] (front row, left), [[Abd as-Salam Arif]] (back row, second from left), [[Abd al-Karim Qasim]] (back row, third from left), and [[Muhammad Najib ar-Ruba'i]] (back row, fifth from left)]]
Following the overthrow of al-Shishakli, Syria held its [[1954 Syrian parliamentary election|first democratic elections]] in five years. The Ba'ath Party, led by Aflaq, al-Bitar and al-Hawrani, had 22 members elected to parliament.{{#tag:ref|Exactly how many seats the Arab Socialist Ba'ath Party won, varies from a low 16 seats to a high 22.
* {{cite book |author=Abdulghani, Jasim |page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=AgMOAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA28 28] |title=Iraq & Iran: The Years of Crisis |publisher=[[Taylor & Francis]] |year=1984 |isbn=978-0801825194}}
* {{cite book |author=Beshara, Adel |page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=2BXdK0Jv1BMC&pg=PA40 40] |title=Lebanon: The Politics of Frustration – The Failed coup of 1961 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |year=2005 |isbn=978-0415351133 |edition=1}}
* {{cite book |author=Commins, Dean |title=Historical Dictionary of Syria |publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield|Scarecrow Press]] |year=2004 |isbn=978-0810849341 |page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=_EhACvcqVXkC&pg=PA66 66]}}|group=note}} This increase in influence can largely be attributed to al-Hawrani – several old ASP strongholds voted for the Ba'ath Party because of al-Hawrani's presence.{{sfn|Commins|2004|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=_EhACvcqVXkC&pg=PA66 66]}} By this time Aflaq was losing much of his power to al-Hawrani and his supporters, who were in a majority in the party. Proof of this was the decision of the Ba'ath Party to collaborate openly with the [[Syrian Communist Party]] (SCP), a move Aflaq opposed.{{sfn|Abdulghani|1984|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=AgMOAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA28 28]}} Aflaq was elected the party's Secretary General of the newly established National Command, a title equivalent to 'party leader', by the party's Second National Congress.{{sfn|Benewick|Green|1988|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=qJrCWS4TU1sC&pg=PA4 4]}}

When, under the [[United Arab Republic]] (UAR), Aflaq was forced by Nasser to dissolve the party, he disbanded the party by himself, instead of convening a congress on the matter.{{sfn|Seale|1990|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6D9EiJKRTHcC&pg=PA98 98]}} The UAR proved to be disastrous for the Ba'ath Party – the party was sidelined to a great extent by Nasser's government. The Ba'ath movement, which in 1958 was on the verge of becoming the dominant Arab nationalist movement, found itself in disarray after three years of [[Nasserism|Nasserist]] rule.{{sfn|Seale|1990|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6D9EiJKRTHcC&pg=PA65 65]}} Only a handful of Ba'athists were given public office in the UAR's government; al-Hawrani became vice president and al-Bitar became Minister of Culture and Guidance.{{sfn|Reich|1990|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=3D5FulN2WqQC&pg=PA109 109]}} Several members, mostly young, blamed Aflaq for this situation; it was he who dissolved the party in 1958 without consulting the National Congress. [[Hafez al-Assad]] and [[Salah Jadid]] amongst others, eventually established the Military Committee to save the Syrian Ba'ath movement from annihilation.{{sfn|Seale|1990|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6D9EiJKRTHcC&pg=PA61 61–62]}} The party's Third National Congress in 1959 supported Aflaq's decision to dissolve the party, but a 1960 National Congress, in which Jadid was a delegate representing the then-unknown Military Committee, reversed the decision and called for the Ba'ath Party's reestablishment. The Congress also decided to improve relations with Nasser by democratising the UAR from within. A faction within the party, led by al-Hawrani, called for Syria's secession.{{sfn|Seale|1990|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6D9EiJKRTHcC&pg=PA66 66]}} When the UAR broke up in 1961, some members applauded the dissolution, such as al-Bitar.{{sfn|Reich|1990|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=3D5FulN2WqQC&pg=PA109 109]}}
[[File:Hawrani Aflaq 1957.jpg|thumb|Aflaq (right) with [[Akram al-Hawrani|al-Hawrani]] in 1957]]
The Ba'ath Party captured 20 seats, down from 22, in the [[1961 Syrian parliamentary election|1961 election]].{{sfn|Nohlen|Florian|Hartmann|2001|p=221}} In 1962, after four years, Aflaq convened the Fifth Congress in [[Homs]]. Al-Hawrani was not invited; cells that had stayed active and defied Aflaq's orders, and Ba'athists who became Nasserists during the period of the UAR, were not invited to the congress. Aflaq was reelected as the National Command's secretary general, and ordered the reestablishment of the Syrian-regional Ba'ath organisation. During the congress, Aflaq and the Military Committee, through [[Muhammad Umran]], made contact for the first time; the committee asked for permission to initiate a coup d'état; Aflaq supported the conspiracy.{{sfn|Seale|1990|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6D9EiJKRTHcC&pg=PA75 75]}} Following the success of the [[February 1963 Iraqi coup d'état]], led by the Ba'ath Party's [[Arab Socialist Ba'ath Party – Iraq Region|Iraqi Regional Branch]], the Military Committee hastily convened to hatch a coup against [[Nazim al-Kudsi]]'s presidency. The [[8th of March Revolution]], a military coup launched in 1963, proved successful, and a Ba'athist government in Syria was established.{{sfn|Seale|1990|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6D9EiJKRTHcC&pg=PA76 76–78]}} The plotters' first order was to establish the [[National Council of the Revolutionary Command]] (NCRC), consisting entirely of Ba'athists and Nasserists, and controlled by military personnel rather than civilians from the very beginning.{{sfn|Seale|1990|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6D9EiJKRTHcC&pg=PA78 78]}}

=== The beginning: 1963–1964 ===
[[File:Michel Aflaq and Salah Jadid in 1963.jpg|thumb|left|Aflaq and [[Salah Jadid]] in 1963, shortly after taking power]]
The relationship between the Ba'athists and the Nasserists was at best, uncomfortable. The Ba'ath Party's rise to power in Iraq and Syria put Nasser, as he put it, "between the hammer and the anvil".{{Citation needed|date=January 2026}} The establishment of a union between Iraq and Syria would weaken his credentials as a pan-Arab leader.{{sfn|Seale|1990|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6D9EiJKRTHcC&pg=PA81 81]}} Nasser launched bitter propaganda attacks against the party; Aflaq was dismissed as an ineffectual theorist who was mocked as a puppet "[[Roman emperor]]" and accused of being a "Cypriot Christian".{{sfn|Seale|1990|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6D9EiJKRTHcC&pg=PA81 81–82]}} In several Ba'ath Party meetings, Aflaq responded with pure anger, and became an anti-Nasserist. Because of the position he took, Aflaq had a falling out with al-Bitar who still believed there was a chance to reestablish good ties with Nasser.{{sfn|Seale|1990|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6D9EiJKRTHcC&pg=PA82 82]}}

The break with Nasser weakened the original leaders of the Ba'ath Party, which in turn gave the Military Committee room to expand. After taking power, the Military Committee looked for theoretical guidance, but instead of going to Aflaq to solve problems (which was usual before), they contacted the party's Marxist faction led by [[Hammud al-Shufi]].{{sfn|Seale|1990|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6D9EiJKRTHcC&pg=PA86 86]}} At the Syrian Ba'athist Regional Congress, the Military Committee "proved" that it was rebelling equally against Aflaq and the traditional leadership, as against their moderate social and economic policies. The Military Committee was bent on removing Aflaq from a position of power, believing that he had become old and frail. At the Sixth National Congress held in October 1963, Aflaq was barely able to hold on to his post as Secretary General – the Marxist factions led by al-Shufi and [[Ali Salih al-Sa'di]], in Syria and Iraq respectively, were the majority group. Another problem facing Aflaq was that several of his colleagues were not elected to party office; for instance, al-Bitar was not reelected to a seat in the National Command. Instead of the traditional civilian leadership, a new leadership consisting of military officers was gradually growing; Jadid and [[Amin al-Hafiz]] from Syria and [[Ahmed Hassan al-Bakr]] and [[Salih Mahdi Ammash]] from Iraq were elected to the National Command. While the Military Committee was in fact taking control over the Ba'ath Party from the civilian leadership, they were sensitive to such criticism, and stated, in an ideological pamphlet, that civilian-military symbiosis was of major importance if socialist reconstruction was to be achieved.{{sfn|Seale|1990|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6D9EiJKRTHcC&pg=PA88 88]}} To the outside world, Aflaq seemed to be in charge. The [[Tunisia]]n newspaper ''{{Interlanguage link|L'Action tunisienne|fr}}'' referred to him as "The philosopher who made two coups [Iraqi and Syrian coups] in a month".{{sfn|Seale|1990|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6D9EiJKRTHcC&pg=PA90 90]}}

The Ba'ath movement was not running as smoothly as the rest of the world believed; the Iraqi Regional Branch was already starting to lose membership. The Iraqi military and the party's militant arm, the [[National Guard (Iraq)|National Guard]], detested each other. Al-Sadi, the Regional Secretary of the Iraqi Regional Branch, was eventually exiled to [[Madrid]], Spain on 11 November by several military officers and moderate Ba'athists.{{sfn|Seale|1990|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6D9EiJKRTHcC&pg=PA90 90–91]}} An anxious Aflaq hastily traveled from Syria and dissolved the [[Regional Command of the Arab Socialist Ba'ath Party – Iraq Region|Regional Command]] of the Iraqi Regional Branch, exclaiming that the National Command would rule Iraq in its place until a new Regional Command was elected. This was not greeted warmly by the majority of Iraqi military officers and Ba'athists – the idea that a Christian was to rule over a Muslim country was considered "insensitive".

The situation in Iraq did not improve, [[Abdul Salam Arif]], the [[President of Iraq]] and a Nasserist, plotted a coup against the Ba'ath Party on 18 November, which succeeded. The dream of cornering Nasser's pan-Arab project was over; instead, it was Nasser and the Nasserists who were cornering the Ba'ath movement. On hearing the news, Aflaq and several Ba'athists fled Iraq for Syria.{{sfn|Seale|1990|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6D9EiJKRTHcC&pg=PA91 91]}}

=== The schism: 1964–1965 ===
After a falling out with the Military Committee, of which he was a member, Muhammad Umran told Aflaq about the committee's secret plans to oust the civilian leadership, led by Aflaq, and take over the Ba'ath Party. Shortly after, Umran was sent into exile as Ambassador to Spain for supporting the Aflaq faction.{{sfn|Seale|1990|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6D9EiJKRTHcC&pg=PA96 96]}} Aflaq responded to the threat posed to his leadership by invoking his office as secretary general, and calling for the National Command to dissolve the [[Regional Command of the Arab Socialist Ba'ath Party – Syria Region|Regional Command]]. He was forced to withdraw his request when the majority of Ba'ath Party members proved to oppose such a move. A contest for power between Aflaq and the Military Committee ensued in the open; but it was a struggle Aflaq was losing.{{sfn|Seale|1990|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6D9EiJKRTHcC&pg=PA96 96]}} It was plain from the very beginning that the initiative lay with the anti-Aflaq forces.{{sfn|Seale|1990|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6D9EiJKRTHcC&pg=PA97 97]}} To counter the military threat, Aflaq invoked party rules and regulations against them. To counter this, the Military Committee befriended a staunchly anti-Aflaq civilian faction calling themselves the "[[Qutriyun|Regionalists]]" – this group had not dissolved their party organisations as ordered by Aflaq in the 1950s.{{sfn|Seale|1990|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6D9EiJKRTHcC&pg=PA97 97]}}

The Regional Congress of the Syrian Regional Branch, in March 1965, devolved power from the center, the National Command, to the Regional Command. From then on, the Regional Secretary of the Regional Command was considered Syria's ''[[ex officio]]'' head of state. The Regional Secretary had the power to appoint the prime minister, the cabinet, the chief of staff and top military commanders. Aflaq was unsettled by the way things were moving, and in May he convened the Eighth National Congress to get a showdown between his followers and those of the Military Committee. However, this never came to fruition. Several civilian members of the National Command, such as the Lebanese [[Jibran Majdalani]] and the Saudi [[Ali Ghannam]], advised caution, believing that if he pressed the Military Committee too hard the military would take over the Syrian Regional Branch, and then the Ba'ath Party – as had happened in Iraq following the ousting of the Iraqi Regional Branch.
Because of their concerns, Aflaq kept quiet. But to his astonishment, keeping quiet caused him to lose his post as Secretary General – Aflaq was succeeded as Secretary General of the National Command by [[Munif al-Razzaz]], a Jordanian of Syrian origin. However, the power between the two camps was unexpectedly reshuffled when [[Amin al-Hafiz]] defected to Aflaq's camp. In contrast to other military officers al-Hafiz had very little influence within or outside the party.{{sfn|Seale|1990|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6D9EiJKRTHcC&pg=PA99 99]}} Al-Hafiz's defection led to a resurgence of activity within Aflaq's faction. Al-Bitar and Umran were brought back from Spain to form a new government.{{sfn|Seale|1990|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6D9EiJKRTHcC&pg=PA100 100–101]}}

=== Downfall: 1966–1968 ===
[[File:Baath Party founder Michel Aflaq with Iraqi President Ahmad Hasan al-Bakr in Baghdad in 1968.jpg|thumb|left|[[Ahmed Hassan al-Bakr]] (left), the Regional Secretary of the Iraqi Ba'ath branch, shaking hands with Aflaq in 1968]]
Al-Razzaz, Aflaq's successor as secretary general, came from the pro-Aflaq faction. With the defection of al-Hafiz, he ordered that the National Command was the ''de jure'' ruling body of the Ba'ath Party. He appointed al-Bitar prime minister, Umran defence minister, [[Mansur al-Atrash]] as Chairman of the [[National Council of the Revolutionary Command]] and al-Hafiz retained his post as [[President of Syria]]. Salah Jadid, the Military Committee's strongman, responded by arresting several Umran supporters. Umran responded by dismissing a handful of pro-Jadid officials. The most important of these dismissals was the removal of [[Ahmad Suwaydani]] from the post of head of the country's military intelligence to head of the Officer Administration.{{sfn|Moubayed|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=sC-xU8QHSooC&pg=PA347 347]}} On 23 February 1966, a [[1966 Syrian coup d'état|coup d'état]] led by Jadid and [[Hafez al-Assad]] overthrew the Syrian Government and the Ba'ath Party leadership.{{sfn|Moubayed|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=sC-xU8QHSooC&pg=PA134 134]}} Aflaq was exiled from Syria, and ordered never to return to his homeland. Members of the party's other factions fled; Aflaq was captured and detained, along with other pro-Aflaq supporters, in a government guest house.{{sfn|Seale|1990|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6D9EiJKRTHcC&pg=PA102 102]}} When the new rulers launched a purge in August that year, Aflaq managed to make his escape, with the help of [[Nasim Al Safarjalani]] and [[Malek Bashour]], both closely trusted friends and colleagues, and hence was able to flee to [[Beirut]], Lebanon,{{sfn|Seale|1990|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=6D9EiJKRTHcC&pg=PA111 111]}} and later to [[Brazil]].{{sfn|Commins|2004|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=_EhACvcqVXkC&pg=PA26 26]}}

Aflaq's downfall caused a split within the Ba'ath Party; the party was ''de facto'' dissolved and two Ba'ath Parties were established, [[Ba'ath Party (Iraq)|one Iraqi-led Ba'ath Party]] and [[Ba'ath Party (Syria)|one Syrian-led Ba'ath Party]]. The Syrian-led party was led by Jadid and his supporters and hailed Zaki al-Arsuzi, the founder of the Arab Ba'ath in 1940, as the father of [[Ba'athism|Ba'athist thought]], while the Iraqi-led party led by [[Ahmed Hassan al-Bakr]] and [[Saddam Hussein]], still proclaimed Aflaq to be the founder of Ba'athist thought.{{sfn|Bengio|1998|p=[https://archive.org/details/saddamswordpolit0000beng/page/218 218]}} In February 1966 at the Ninth National Congress, held after the coup which ousted the pro-Aflaq faction, the Iraqi delegation split with the Syrian Ba'athists. The Iraqis held the ''true'' Ninth National Congress in February 1968 in Beirut,{{sfn|Kostiner|1998|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=YQb1Ilj2U7EC&pg=PA36 36]}} and elected Aflaq as Secretary General of the National Command.{{sfn|Moubayed|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=sC-xU8QHSooC&pg=PA347 347]}} Aflaq's election to the secretary generalship also proved to be his final break with al-Bitar; before the congress convened al-Bitar announced that he had left the Ba'ath Party and given up on the Ba'athist movement as a whole.{{sfn|Reich|1990|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=3D5FulN2WqQC&pg=PA110 110]}}

=== Iraqi-led Ba'ath Party: 1968–1989 ===
[[File:Baath Party founder Michel Aflaq with Iraqi President Saddam Hussein in 1988.jpg|thumb|Michel Aflaq in conversation with [[Saddam Hussein]] in 1988]]

Aflaq moved to [[Baghdad]] following his reelection to the secretary generalship in February 1968. He stayed there until 1970, when [[Black September]] happened, he criticized the Ba'ath leadership for doing too little to help the [[Palestine Liberation Organisation]] during the conflict.{{sfn|Moubayed|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=sC-xU8QHSooC&pg=PA347 347]}} During the conflict, Aflaq lobbied extensively for [[Yasser Arafat]] and the PLO. Aflaq wanted Iraqi intervention; al-Bakr, however, refused to get Iraq involved in such a conflict. Because of this, Aflaq returned to Lebanon in self-imposed exile.{{sfn|Moubayed|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=sC-xU8QHSooC&pg=PA347 347]}} The government of Hafez al-Assad, the President of Syria, condemned Aflaq to death in absentia in 1971.{{sfn|Tucker|2010|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=U05OvsOPeKMC&pg=PA30 30]}}

After four years of self-imposed exile Aflaq returned to Iraq in 1974, a year before the [[Lebanese Civil War]] broke out.{{sfn|Shair|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=D3kqgioYJisC&pg=PA39 39]}} He refrained from taking part in Iraqi politics. He published several works during this period, the most notable being ''The Struggle Against Distorting the Movement of Arab Revolution'' in 1975. Aflaq regained some of his influence when he befriended Saddam Hussein, President of Iraq from 1979 until 2003. During the [[Iran–Iraq War]] the Iranian leadership accused Hussein of being under the control of a Christian, and Aflaq himself was labelled "a Christian infidel".{{sfn|Moubayed|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=sC-xU8QHSooC&pg=PA347 347]}} Effectively, throughout his tenure as secretary general in Iraq, Aflaq was given all due honour as the founder of the Ba'ath movement, but on policy-making, he was ignored.{{sfn|Shair|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=D3kqgioYJisC&pg=PA39 39]}}

== Death and funeral==
Aflaq died on 23 June 1989 in Paris, after undergoing heart surgery there.{{sfn|Tucker|2010|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=U05OvsOPeKMC&pg=PA30 30]}} Upon his death, he was given a state funeral. A large [[tomb]] and [[mausoleum]] were erected to form a [[shrine]] for him. The tomb, widely regarded as a work of great artistic merit, designed by Iraqi architect [[Rifat Chadirji]], was located on the western grounds of the Ba'ath Party Pan-Arab Headquarters, at the intersection of [[Al-Kindi street]] and the Qadisiyyah Expressway overpass. Although there were rumors and accusations that his tomb was destroyed during the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|2003 Iraq War]], the burial chamber and building above it were left untouched. Its blue-tiled dome can be seen above the concrete T-walls surrounding the Camp's perimeter.<ref>[http://www.mideastweb.org/Middle-East-Encyclopedia/michel_aflaq.htm Michel Aflaq] // Encyclopedia of the Middle East. Ami Isseroff, 14 October 2008</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20140315100849/http://carnegieendowment.org/syriaincrisis/?fa=54844 The Miserable Afterlife of Michel Aflaq] // Carnegie Endowment for International Peace. By Aron Lund, 10 March 2014</ref><ref>Ryan, Missy. [https://web.archive.org/web/20090925184746/http://blogs.reuters.com/global/2009/09/20/aflaq-symbol-of-iraq-and-syrias-shared-past/ "Aflaq, symbol of Iraq and Syria's shared past"], ''Global News Journal'', 20 September 2009</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160811010412/http://blogs.reuters.com/global/files/2009/09/michel-aflaq-025.jpg The blue-domed memorial] to honour [[Ba'ath Party]] founder Michel Aflaq</ref>

== Alleged conversion to Islam ==
[[File:Aflaq funeral.jpg|thumbnail|Aflaq's coffin carried by Saddam Hussein and [[Izzat Ibrahim al-Douri|Izzat Ibrahim ad-Douri]]]]
Saddam Hussein claimed that Aflaq converted to [[Islam]] before his death. According to anonymous Western diplomats, Aflaq's own family disagreed with that claim;{{sfn|Harris|1997|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=D3kqgioYJisC&pg=PA39 39]}} however, Aflaq's son, Iyad, confirmed that his father thought about conversion in 1980.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alarabiya.net/articles/2007/05/07/34221|title=عائلة مؤسس &quot;البعث&quot; تؤكد وجود رسالة تثبت اعتناقه الإسلام|date=7 May 2007|website=العربية}}</ref> Upon his disputed conversion, he supposedly adopted "[[Ahmed]]" as a first name.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Böwering |editor1-first=Gerhard |editor2-last=Crone |editor2-first=Patricia |editor3-last=Mirza |editor3-first=Mahan |title=The Princeton Encyclopedia of Islamic Political Thought |year=2013 |publisher=Princeton University Press |isbn=9780691134840 |page=22 |edition=illustrated}}</ref> According to the German orientalists Martin Robbe and Gerhard Höpp, the conversion happened before 1988.<ref>Martin Robbe, Gerhard Höpp: ''Welt des Islam – Geschichte und Alltag einer Religion'', page 149. Urania-Verlag, Leipzig/Jena/Berlin 1988</ref> Regardless of the disagreements about his religion, he was given an Islamic funeral.{{sfn|Shair|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=D3kqgioYJisC&pg=PA39 39]}} According to the Berkley Center, anonymous members of Aflaq's family claimed that Aflaq's conversion was a "lie" made up by Saddam Hussein which he used as a tool to distance Ba'athism from Christianity.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://berkleycenter.georgetown.edu/resources/people/michel-aflaq |title=Michel Aflaq |publisher=[[Georgetown University]] |access-date=21 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130729203338/http://berkleycenter.georgetown.edu/resources/people/michel-aflaq |archive-date=29 July 2013}}</ref> The tomb constructed on the orders of Hussein was later used as a military barrack by American soldiers after the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|2003 American invasion of Iraq]] for troops stationed within the [[Green Zone]].<ref>{{cite web |author1=Robertson, Campbell |author2=Farrell, Stephen |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/01/world/middleeast/01greenzone.html |title=Green Zone, Heart of U.S. Occupation, Reverts to Iraqi Control |work=The New York Times |access-date=21 December 2011 |date=31 December 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=House Diggity |url=https://hdiggity.blogspot.com/2006/05/foosball-and-baathism.html |title=Foosball and Baathism |work=House in Iraq |access-date=3 March 2012|date=23 May 2006}}</ref> Aflaq's family reported that the tomb was badly damaged during the invasion.<ref>{{cite web |last=Fisk |first=Robert |author-link=Robert Fisk |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/opinion/commentators/fisk/robert-fisk-saddam-revisited-as-iraq-accuses-syria-of-sheltering-baathist-bombers-1785453.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220514/https://www.independent.co.uk/opinion/commentators/fisk/robert-fisk-saddam-revisited-as-iraq-accuses-syria-of-sheltering-baathist-bombers-1785453.html |archive-date=14 May 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |title=Saddam revisited as Iraq accuses Syria of sheltering Baathist bombers |publisher=[[Independent Print Limited]] |work=The Independent |location=UK |access-date=21 December 2011 |date=11 September 2009}}</ref>

